1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, and a false sense of security... only to take all of it back with interest at the right time! }
1... e5
{ After  1...d6  2.Bb2  Black is well advised to transpose to 1...e5 territory! }
2. Bb2
{ The fight is already beginning. Black has to make a decision on how to defend the pawn. }
2... Nc6 3. c4
{ Inspired by Fischer's direction, we fight for the control of the central square on d5. }
3... d5
{ Honestly I couldn't believe my eyes when even this was a decent option!! } 4.
cxd5 Qxd5 5. Nc3 Qd6 6. Rc1 { Occupying the only semi-open file. } 6... Nf6 7.
Nf3 a6 8. Qc2
{ Preventing any e4-ideas now that Nb5 doesn't work for us anymore. } 8... Bg4
9. e3 { Activating the bishop. } 9... Nb4
{ Getting in this important move before we have time to play a3 and stop it permanently. }
10. Qb1 Bxf3 11. gxf3 O-O-O 12. Rd1
{ Here we shouldn't sacrifice our d2-pawn as Black king will be quite safe on the queenside. }
12... Be7 13. a3 { Time to go to the endgame! } 13... Nd3+
{ Going back to c6 would be in our favour. } 14. Bxd3 Qxd3 15. Qxd3 Rxd3 16.
Ke2
{ I like such endgames for White since our king is well placed in the center and we can create play on both the kingside and queenside. }
