[Black "The brave and the bold #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, and a false sense of security... only to take all of it back with interest at the right time! }
1... e5
{ After  1...d6  2.Bb2  Black is well advised to transpose to 1...e5 territory! }
2. Bb2
{ The fight is already beginning. Black has to make a decision on how to defend the pawn. }
2... Nc6 3. c4
{ Inspired by Fischer's direction, we fight for the control of the central square on d5. }
3... Nf6
{ Continuing with development and Black is preparing to break with d5. } 4. e3
d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. a3
{ An important move restricting Black's ideas with Ndb4. } 6... a6
{ This would be a very respectable and natural choice in blitz. } 7. Nf3
{ I like this direction more, as we can get an advantage if Black plays natural moves. }
7... Bd6 8. d3 { Stopping any e4 ideas. If Black goes for... } 8... Qe7 9. Nbd2
{ We delay Be2 as the bishop has more amazing prospects in a different dimension! }
9... g5 10. g3
{ Utilizing the fact that we haven't played Be2 to the fullest. } 10... h5 11.
Bg2 h4 { Brutally stopping us from playing h4. } 12. Nxh4
{ Provoking a tactical operation by trying to win a pawn using the unprotected knight on d5. }
12... Nxe3 { Black also grabs a pawn to retain material equality. } 13. fxe3
gxh4 14. Bxc6+
{ Ruining Black's structure and the knight will have a strong hold on c4. }
14... bxc6 15. Qf3 Bd7 16. Nc4
{ The knight is well placed on c4 with pressure on e5 and can jump to a5 to target c6-pawn. }
16... hxg3 17. hxg3 Rxh1+ 18. Qxh1 { The dust has settled... } 18... O-O-O 19.
O-O-O
{ Although the comp gives equality, I feel the difference in the safety of the king makes sure we can play more freely. }
