1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, and a false sense of security... only to take all of it back with interest at the right time! }
1... e5
{ After  1...d6  2.Bb2  Black is well advised to transpose to 1...e5 territory! }
2. Bb2
{ The fight is already beginning. Black has to make a decision on how to defend the pawn. }
2... Nc6 3. c4
{ Inspired by Fischer's direction, we fight for the control of the central square on d5. }
3... Nf6
{ Continuing with development and Black is preparing to break with d5. } 4. e3
d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. a3
{ An important move restricting Black's ideas with Ndb4. } 6... Be7
{ The second most popular line is this very soft move. } 7. Qc2
{ The best square for the queen. } 7... O-O 8. Nf3
{ It is important to note that in the Be7 line, we avoid making the d3 move. }
8... Re8 9. d3 { Similar concept! } 9... Bg5
{ With the nasty idea of Bxe3 fxe3 Nxe3 followed by Nd4 with clear control over the central affairs. }
10. Nc3 { Avoiding any tricks on e3. } 10... Nxc3 11. Qxc3 Bf5 12. Rc1
{ Maintaining pressure along the c-file. } 12... Bf6 13. Nd2
{ Aimed against e4 ideas. } 13... Qd5 14. Qc2
{ Not good is  14.e4  Qd7  15.exf5  e4  this was Black's concept 😀 with a winning attack. }
14... Be6 15. Qc5 { Exchanging queens in order to develop the f1-bishop. 😀 }
15... Red8 16. Qxd5 Rxd5 17. Be2 Rad8 18. O-O
{ With a decent position and the rest will be up to to you guys! } *

