1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, and a false sense of security... only to take all of it back with interest at the right time! }
1... e5
{ After  1...d6  2.Bb2  Black is well advised to transpose to 1...e5 territory! }
2. Bb2
{ The fight is already beginning. Black has to make a decision on how to defend the pawn. }
2... Nc6 3. c4
{ Inspired by Fischer's direction, we fight for the control of the central square on d5. }
3... Nf6
{ Continuing with development and Black is preparing to break with d5. } 4. e3
d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. a3
{ An important move restricting Black's ideas with Ndb4. } 6... Bd6 7. d3
{ I hope that with my course, I can change the tide and make this the mainline and outlast the fake popularity of Qc2 😀.   The most popular line is  7.Qc2  and I would have loved to recommend it... if only it had worked!  This is the only move that has been covered in Logozar's course:  7...Qe7!  I couldn't find any way to even equalize here 😀. Not something we want to do with our amazing line!  8.Nf3   After  8.d3  f5  Black is slightly better.  8...e4  9.Nd4  Nxd4  10.Bxd4  O-O  maybe White can equalize, but it is not something I would recommend! }
7... O-O 8. Nf3 f5 9. Nbd2 { One prophylactic approach could be... } 9... a5
10. g3 { This move always kills Black's chances of a kingside attack. } 10...
Qe7 11. Nc4 { Aimed against e4 ideas. } 11... Be6 12. Bg2 f4 13. exf4
{ The isolani on d3 will be irrelevant in the fight! } 13... exf4 14. O-O
{ With a nice game with play along the e-file and activity along the long diagonals. }
