1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, a false sense of security... Only to take all of them back with interest at the right time! }
1... e5
{ After  1...d6  2.Bb2  Black is well advised to transpose to 1...e5 territory! }
2. Bb2 d6 3. c4
{ I feel this is the most critical attempt, but for some reason, it is only the 3rd most popular move after e3 and g3!  This is less commital as we keep all options involving both e3 and g3 ideas open. }
3... g6 { Black wants to get Bg7-f5 etc. } 4. d4
{ We don't give Black time to execute any of his plans! 😀 } 4... Bg7 5. dxe5
{ We are heading for forcing directions  unlike moves like e3 or Nf3 to provoke Black into making some positional concessions! }
5... Nd7 6. Nf3 dxe5 7. e3 { Preparing Be2 and Nc3 ideas } 7... Ne7 8. Nc3
{ Aiming for the juicy squares on d5 and e4. } 8... O-O 9. Qd2
{ Protecting the bishop and preventing e4 ideas from Black. } 9... Nc6 10. Be2
{ This position is favourable for us, due to the better control over the d-file and the potential outpost on d5. }
