[White "Quickstarter Guide 1.b3"]
[Black "The brave and the bold II #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, a false sense of security... Only to take all of them back with interest at the right time! }
1... e5
{ After  1...d6  2.Bb2  Black is well advised to transpose to 1...e5 territory! }
2. Bb2 d6 3. c4
{ I feel this is the most critical attempt, but for some reason, it is only the 3rd most popular move after e3 and g3! This is less commital as we keep all options involving both e3 and g3 ideas open. }
3... c5
{ Now we are suddenly thrown into the English Symmetry positions! Our play is based on the weak d5-square. }
4. Nc3
{ I am putting  4.e3  here to show why it is not so good.  4...Nc6  5.Nf3  g6  6.d4  exd4  7.exd4  Bg7  This is clearly equal. There is no need to go for this, trust me I am talking from experience! 😀 }
4... g6 5. g3
{ The fight for the control of the d5-square begins... Another possible move order is  5.d3  Nc6  6.g3  Nge7  7.Bg2  Bg7  with a transposition to our main line. }
5... Bg7 6. Bg2 Nc6 7. d3
{ We choose a d3 and Nf3 set-up which is the optimum formation for the middlegame battle. }
7... Nge7
{ 7...f5  I recently came across this direction of playing first f7-f5 and then Ng8-f6 leading to entirely new territory. Black is trying to gain a lot of control over the center and then continue with development of the knight.  8.Qd2!  N Based on a crazy and concrete plan!  8...Nf6  9.f4!  A stunning concept where we are also fighting for the central control in a different and much cooler way.  9...O-O  10.Nh3!  The knight is very nicely placed on h3 where it doesn't get in the way of any piece. We follow it up with short castling with a slight pull due to our more actively placed pieces.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pp3pbp/2np2p1/2p1p3/2P5/1PNP2P1/PB2PPBP/R2QK1NR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@ If Black goes  7...Nf6  then the knight on f6 is clearly misplaced.  8.Nf3  O-O  9.O-O  h6  Black is preparing Bc8-e6.  10.Nd2  This is the ideal place for our knight in this line.  10...Be6  11.Nde4!  A very nice move stopping Black from achieving the d6-d5 break and eventually one day we will get one of our knights to the d5-square. }
8. Nf3 O-O
{ If Black tries to be foolish and goes for long castling... you can just play a3-b4 and mate him for me! 😀 }
9. O-O
{ This seems like a very playable position for White because we have the d5-square for free while Black doesn't have the d4-square.  So all in all, I think the extra tempo that being White gives us means something here. I got a lot of useful ideas and direction by checking out Demuth's 'Modernized Reti' which covers this position quite well. I recommend it to anyone who wants to learn the Reti! 😀. The move order arises from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  c5  2.c4  Nc6  3.b3  e5  4.Bb2  d6  5.Nc3  g6  6.g3  Bg7  7.d3  Nge7  8.Bg2  O-O  9.O-O  in his book. }
9... h6 10. Nd2 Be6 11. a3
{ Signal to attack! It is very nice to know that Black can never fully prevent b4, since a5 would seriously compromise his entire position and create irreparable weaknesses. }
11... Qd7 12. Nd5 Rab8 13. e3 b5 14. Qc2 f5 15. Rae1
{ Followed by f4 and an epic fight coming up. Also, one funny idea is to play Qc1-a1 to put more pressure on the long diagonal. }
