[White "Quickstarter Guide 1.b3"]
[Black "The brave and the bold II #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, a false sense of security... Only to take all of them back with interest at the right time! }
1... e5
{ After  1...d6  2.Bb2  Black is well advised to transpose to 1...e5 territory! }
2. Bb2 d6 3. c4
{ I feel this is the most critical attempt, but for some reason, it is only the 3rd most popular move after e3 and g3! This is less commital as we keep all options involving both e3 and g3 ideas open. }
3... Nf6 4. Nc3 { We keep our kingside development plans hidden. } 4... g6 5.
d4 { Strike them when it's hot! } 5... exd4 6. Qxd4 Bg7 7. Qe3+
{ Provoking Qe7 which gives the better endgame or Be6 where the bishop is slightly misplaced and can't head to the h1-a8 diagonal!   7.g3  O-O  is usually seen, but I think Black is not doing so bad! }
7... Be6 8. Rd1
{ One of Black's main idea is to prepare d5 in some lines due to our lazy development and hence we need to fight against it. }
8... O-O 9. g3 { The best place for the f1-bishop... In this line and beyond! }
9... c6
{ 9...Nc6  transposes to the line with 6... Nc6 which we will examinehere. }
10. Nh3 { The knight is coming...to f4! } 10... d5
{ Black could try a direct confrontation in the center. } 11. Nf4 Bd7 12. cxd5
{ GREEDY VD! } 12... Nxd5 13. Nfxd5 cxd5 14. Rxd5
{ No guts no glory! - Vidit Gujarathi, 2021. } 14... Qb6 15. Qxb6 axb6 16. Rd2
{ We have a healthy extra pawn... keeping the rook on the best square along the d-file and one day we will develop our pieces! You can count on it! }
