1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, a false sense of security... Only to take all of them back with interest at the right time! }
1... c5 2. Bb2 b6
{ This will lead to a slightly better version than the main line. } 3. e4 Nc6
{ With this move order, Black stops us from achieving d4 followed by Qd2 which is very advantageous for us. }
4. Nf3 Bb7 { 4...e6  5.Nc3  would eventually transpose to the same. } 5. Nc3 e6
6. d4
{ Opening up the centre to capitalize on our positional trumps and to put pressure on d6. }
6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nf6 8. Nxc6 { In order to facilitate our next move. } 8...
Bxc6 9. Bd3
{ We managed to blunt the c6-bishop while keeping our bishop at full power! }
9... Qc7 10. Qd2 b5 { If Black plays slowly, we have a slight pull. } 11. O-O-O
{ First getting our king to safety on the queenside, since eventually, we will have to target the Black king with pawn storms when he goes to the kingside. }
11... a6 12. Rhe1 { Bringing in our last sleeping reserve. } 12... b4 13. Nd5
{ Oh yeah! } 13... Nxd5 14. exd5 Bxd5 15. Qg5
{ What a powerful position for us with a very strong attack! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide 1.b3"]
[Black "The brave and the copycat #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, a false sense of security... Only to take all of them back with interest at the right time! }
1... b6 { Black doesn't want to think on his own, and instead just copies us! }
2. e4
{ We muddle up Black's lazy plans. The alternative  2.Bb2  Bb7  seems quite easy for Black and frankly, not very challenging. }
2... e5 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Bc4
{ We immediately focus on the matter at hand - the f7-square! Black really can't develop Nf6 due to the huge threat with Ng5. 😀 }
4... Bb7 5. O-O g6 6. d4
{ Striking in the center before Black has time to complete his fianchetto! }
6... exd4 7. c3
{ Opening up the position with maximum speed in order to utilize Black's development issues. }
7... dxc3 8. Nxc3 Bg7 9. Bg5
{ Is clearly winning for White due to the weak dark squares, underdeveloped pieces and weak king. For example, play could continue: }
9... Bf6 10. Bxf6 Nxf6 11. e5 Nh5 12. Qd2
{ With a winning advantage. Black can't castle as that would allow Qh6 followed by Ng5. }
