1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, a false sense of security... Only to take all of them back with interest at the right time! }
1... b6 { Black doesn't want to think on his own, and instead just copies us! }
2. e4
{ We muddle up Black's lazy plans. The alternative  2.Bb2  Bb7  seems quite easy for Black and frankly, not very challenging. }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3 e6 4. Bb2
{ Now that the symmetry is broken, it is time to bring out our mighty bishop. }
4... Nf6 5. e5 { Gaining an important hook in the center. } 5... Ne4 6. Nxe4
Bxe4 7. h4
{ A brilliant idea, preparing to brutally attack Black on the kingside @@StartBracket@@even if he goes for long castling@@EndBracket@@!!😀 }
7... d6 8. exd6 { Happily obliging to activate our long diagonal. } 8... Qxd6
9. Nf3 h6
{ To prevent any Ng5 jumps... But unfortunately for Black, that wasn't our only intention! }
10. Ne5
{ Since Ng5 was no longer possible, the knight finds itself sitting very nicely in the center of the board preparing Bb5+ ideas. }
10... Nd7 11. Qe2 { Giving Black no time to take on e5. } 11... Bb7 12. Rh3
{ Another remarkable use of rooks made possible thanks to h4! Thanks to the threat of Rd3, we are just clearly better. }
