1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, and a false sense of security... only to take all of it back with interest at the right time! }
1... Nf6 2. Bb2 g6 { 'Two can play this game!' } 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3
{ We just take it one step further and aim for a double fianchetto! } 4... O-O
5. Bg2
{ This is a major tabiya, there are many ways for Black to continue here. }
5... c5 6. c4
{ Stopping Black from achieving both c5 and d5. It is the essential point in our strategy. }
6... Nc6 7. O-O d5 8. cxd5
{ We can never allow Black to achieve the d4 advance as that would reduce our b2-bishop's potential. }
8... Nxd5 9. Bxg7 Kxg7 10. d4 { Opening up the centre and the game. } 10...
cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4+ Nf6 13. Qe5
{ An epic positional trap after which Black is just busted. I came across this idea during my research via books on 1. b3.  I wholeheartedly recommend the following book from which I learnt lots of nice concepts and ideas 'Winning quickly with 1.b3 and 1...b6' by Odessky. }
13... Qd6 14. Qxd6 exd6 15. Nc3
{ Our ideas are doubling on the d-file and expanding on the kingside. } 15...
Rb8 16. Rfd1 Rd8 17. h3 { Preparing g4. } 17... h5 18. Nb5 { Winning a pawn. }
*

