1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, a false sense of security... Only to take all of them back with interest at the right time! }
1... Nf6 2. Bb2 g6 { 'Two can play this game!' } 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3
{ We just take it one step further and aim for a double fianchetto! } 4... O-O
5. Bg2
{ This is a major tabiya, there are many ways for Black to continue here. }
5... d5 6. c4
{ Attacking the centre before Black can comfortably stabilize it. } 6... dxc4
7. bxc4 c5 8. O-O
{ Since we have an extra pawn in the centre, I tend to favour our chances. }
8... Nc6 9. Ne5
{ I like this direction, because most of my opponent's would always take on e5 after which we are just better! }
9... Na5 10. Qc2 Ng4
{ Black is trying to neutralize our center control by challenging the e5-knight in the most active way possible. }
11. Nd3
{ Trying to keep as many pieces as possible and also targetting one of the few weaknesses in Black's camp which is the c5-pawn before he has time to play Rb8-b6. }
11... Bxb2 12. Qxb2 Nxc4 13. Qc3
{ Let's look at sample lines as to how play could continue. } 13... Nd6 14.
Nxc5 Rb8 15. d3 { Finishing development. } 15... b6 16. Qb2 Qc7 17. Nb3 Bb7 18.
e4
{ With a slight edge due to the extra pawn in the centre which counts for something and also after h3, Black has to go Nh6. }
