[Black "The brave and the KID III #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, a false sense of security... Only to take all of them back with interest at the right time! }
1... Nf6 2. Bb2 g6 { 'Two can play this game!' } 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3
{ We just take it one step further and aim for a double fianchetto! } 4... O-O
5. Bg2
{ This is a major tabiya, there are many ways for Black to continue here. }
5... d5 6. c4
{ Attacking the centre before Black can comfortably stabilize it. } 6... c6
{ It's like Black is saying 'I am a very solid player!'... Nimzo-Larsen players would reply 'We don't care!' }
7. O-O
{ We have reached a slightly more pleasant version of the Grunfeld g3-system. One prophylactic and futuristic noob went for }
7... Re8 { which is surprisingly quite popular! } 8. d4 Bf5 9. e3
{ The typical move to support the center and clear the e2-square for queen. }
9... Nbd7 10. Qe2 { What we say...we do! } 10... dxc4
{ Black gives away the tension in the center in order to prepare a nasty break! }
11. Qxc4 e5 { This thrust was his point. } 12. dxe5 Ng4 13. e6
{ Only way otherwise we could easily end up worse if we allow a knight to come to e5. }
13... Bxe6
{ The bishop also has lost his control over the d3 square which works in our favour. }
14. Qe2 Bxb2 15. Qxb2
{ with a slightly more pleasant middlegame due to the outpost on d4 for the knight and the central pawn majority. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide 1.b3"]
[Black "The English way #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre with a false sense of security, only to take it all back with interest at the right time! }
1... c5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. c4
{ The move order is very important, we delay Nf3 for the time being. } 3... Nf6
4. e3
{ 4.Bxf6  gxf6  5.Nc3  with a strategical fight. To be honest I wouldn't mind trying this as White!  5...e6  6.e3  with a pleasant advantage.   5...h5!  Black has to do this, otherwise he gets slightly worse.  6.h4!  Fixing the pawn on h5 and making it a future target for our pieces.  6...d6  7.g3  with play on the light squares. }
4... e6 5. Nf3
{ After  5...d5  6.cxd5  either recapture will lead to the QGD chapter. } 5...
b6
{ This is slightly different than 4...b6 as we have already committed the knight to f3. }
6. g3 { If Black strikes in the centre with } 6... d5 7. Bg2 Ba6
{ I don't really know if the bishop is better placed on a6! } 8. O-O dxc4 9.
bxc4 { Already we have a big advantage! } 9... Bxc4
{ Otherwise there was no point in taking on c4 😀 } 10. d3
{ This is not easy to find unless you know it 😀. } 10... Qxd3 11. Nfd2
{ A very nice discovered attack! } 11... Rc8 12. Re1
{ Preparing the nasty Bf1 winning the c4-bishop. } 12... b5
{ Only move which doesn't lose immediately. } 13. a4
{ Breaking the support of c4-bishop. } 13... a6 14. Bxf6
{ Time to be greedy and get back what we have sacrificed! } 14... gxf6 15.
Bxc6+ Rxc6 16. Qf3
{ with a clear advantage thanks to weak king @@StartBracket@@side@@EndBracket@@ and the underdeveloped pieces. }
*

