[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Brave and The Bold: 1.b3 e5 2.Bb2 Nc6"]
[Black "3.c4 f5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre with a false sense of security, only to take it all back with interest at the right time! }
1... e5
{ This is one of the most direct attempts and the most principled way to play against the Nimzo-Larsen.   1...Nc6  2.Bb2  will transpose. }
2. Bb2
{ The fight is already beginning. Black has to make a decision on how to defend the pawn. }
2... Nc6 3. c4
{ Inspired by Fischer's direction, we fight for the control of the central square on d5. }
3... f5
{ Spassky has tried this move. Black is also trying to fight for space and initiative on the kingside. }
4. e3 { One day Winter and d4 is coming! } 4... Nf6 5. Nc3
{ I think in these e5 lines, we should delay the development of the kingside knight to avoid any tempi for Black attacking it with e4.   Also, it is still too early for the center break with  5.d4  , since Black can react with  5...exd4  6.exd4  Bb4+  followed by Ne4 ideas. This is possible because Black has not committed to d6 yet. }
5... g6
{ After  5...a6  a funny prophylactic move, waiting for us to commit d4  6.Be2!  is a useful developing move and we go for d4 next with a clear advantage. The key is always to delay the development of the g1-knight which is waiting for new career paths along the h3-f4 direction if Black commits e4. }
6. d4
{ Attack on the Titans... I mean the center, before Black can set up his configuration! }
6... d6
{ Or  6...e4  7.Nh3!  With a big advantage, one of the points of delaying g1-knight development. We follow it up with Nf4-h4 and then go long castling with an assault on the kingside! }
7. dxe5 Nxe5 8. g3
{ The fianchetto of the bishop will be the best way to activate it with full power! }
8... Bg7 9. Bg2 O-O 10. Nge2
{ We prefer this way of development as the knight will be well placed on f4 and since we have more space, as a rule it is better to avoid exchanges of pieces. }
10... c6 { In order to neutralize the Catalan bishop. } 11. O-O
{ We follow it up with Qc2-Rad1 with a very nice advantage due to the weak d6-pawn and lack of active ideas for Black. }
*

