{ We just give Black the centre with a false sense of security, only to take it all back with interest at the right time! }
1... e5
{ This is one of the most direct attempts and the most principled way to play against the Nimzo-Larsen.   1...Nc6  2.Bb2  will transpose. }
2. Bb2
{ The fight is already beginning. Black has to make a decision on how to defend the pawn. }
2... Nc6 3. c4
{ Inspired by Fischer's direction, we fight for the control of the central square on d5. }
3... g6
{ Black is getting ready to neutralize White's pressure along the long diagonal with a warrior of his own! }
4. e3 { Slowly but surely preparing to assault the centre with d4. } 4... Bg7
{ After  4...d6  5.Nf3  Bg7  we transpose to4...Bg7/5...d6 } 5. Nf3
{ Increasing the central control... } 5... Nge7 6. d4
{ It is time since we can't allow Black to achieve d5! During Dubov's banter blitz I chose  6.Nc3  against him  6...O-O  7.Be2  d5  8.cxd5  Nxd5  @@StartBracket@@I had managed to confuse my recommendation from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.b3  e5  2.Bb2  d6  lines.😀@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2pbp/2n3p1/3np3/8/1PN1PN2/PB1PBPPP/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nxd5  Qxd5  Black was already superior in AD - Dubov Banter Blitz 2020  10.d3  e4!  a simple shot winning a piece!  11.Bxg7  exf3  12.Bxf8  @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppp2pBp/2n3p1/3q4/8/1P1PPp2/P3BPPP/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bxf3  Qa5+  was the trick I had missed! Shameful 😀 @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b2Bk1/ppp2p1p/2n3p1/3q4/8/1P1PPp2/P3BPPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...fxe2  13.Qxe2  Qxg2  14.Qb2!  Finding the only way to complicate the issues at least a bit!  14...Kxf8  would have given a big advantage to him!   @@StartFEN@@r1b2Bk1/ppp2p1p/2n3p1/8/8/1P1PP3/PQ3PqP/R3K2R b KQ - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Qxh1+  In recent times Dubov had been disrespecting the might of the queen and went for  15.Kd2  Qxa1  16.Qxa1  Kxf8  with a balanced endgame where I went for some dirty flagging and won 😀 @@StartBracket@@kind of ashamed to put the game here@@EndBracket@@. }
6... e4 7. Ng5
{ This is much stronger than the usually seen Nfd2 as the knight needs to reach his destined outpost on f4 where it will influence the kingside affairs. }
7... d5 8. cxd5 Qxd5 9. h4
{ White has the dual threat of Nc3 winning the e4-pawn and Bc4 winning the f7-pawn! All these have been made possible thanks to the mighty jump of the knight to g5! }
9... Qa5+ { Desperately trying to hold on to the pawn on e4. } 10. Nc3 f5 11.
a3
{ With advantage, preparing to attack the queen with b4 and also getting Bc4 ideas ready! }
