[Round "?"]
[White "The Brave and The Bold: 1.b3 e5 2.Bb2 Nc6"]
[Black "4.e3 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.a3 Be6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre with a false sense of security, only to take it all back with interest at the right time! }
1... e5
{ This is one of the most direct attempts and the most principled way to play against the Nimzo-Larsen.   1...Nc6  2.Bb2  will transpose. }
2. Bb2
{ The fight is already beginning. Black has to make a decision on how to defend the pawn. }
2... Nc6 3. c4
{ Inspired by Fischer's direction, we fight for the control of the central square on d5. }
3... Nf6
{ Continuing with development and Black is preparing to break with d5. } 4. e3
{ We open up the path of the f1-bishop while keeping our development schemes of the knight's hidden for the time being. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. a3
{ An important move restricting Black's ideas with Ndb4. } 6... Be6
{ Black is trying to go for an English attack! } 7. Qc2 Qd7
{ 7...f6  8.b4  Qd7  9.Nf3  will transpose to our mainline here. } 8. Nf3 f6 9.
b4 { Signalling the start of the war! } 9... Bf5
{ At first the comp likes this move. } 10. e4 Bg6 11. b5
{ If one attack doesn't work, let's go for the second. 😀 } 11... Nd8 12. d4
{ Opening up the position, since Black is completely misplaced. } 12... exd4
13. h4 { Preparing to break the pin in style! } 13... Nf4 14. Nxd4
{ We got our pawn back. 😀 } 14... Nde6 15. Nxe6 Nxe6 16. Nc3
{ Development is our priority! } 16... O-O-O 17. h5 { Go back, Simon! } 17...
Nd4 { Or  17...Bf7  18.Nd5  Nc5  19.O-O-O  with chaos on the board. } 18. O-O-O
{ We never said 'We would move the queen'! } 18... Nxc2 19. Rxd7 Rxd7
{ After  19...Kxd7  20.hxg6  Nxa3  21.gxh7  I would prefer White here due to the advanced pawn on h7. 😀 }
20. hxg6 Nxa3 21. Rxh7 { Here it is better to take with the rook! } 21... Rg8
22. g3 { And the bishop will reign supreme from the h3-c8 diagonal. } *

