[White "The Brave and The Bold: 1.b3 e5 2.Bb2 Nc6"]
[Black "4.e3 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.a3 g6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre with a false sense of security, only to take it all back with interest at the right time! }
1... e5
{ This is one of the most direct attempts and the most principled way to play against the Nimzo-Larsen.   1...Nc6  2.Bb2  will transpose. }
2. Bb2
{ The fight is already beginning. Black has to make a decision on how to defend the pawn. }
2... Nc6 3. c4
{ Inspired by Fischer's direction, we fight for the control of the central square on d5. }
3... Nf6
{ Continuing with development and Black is preparing to break with d5. } 4. e3
{ We open up the path of the f1-bishop while keeping our development schemes of the knight's hidden for the time being. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. a3
{ An important move restricting Black's ideas with Ndb4. } 6... g6
{ There are many who would prefer to do a kingside fianchetto...   Or  6...f6  we need not be bothered with this move as  7.b4  Be6  only leads to...  8.Nf3  with a transposition tothis variation after  8...Qd7  9.Qc2 }
7. d3 { Our concept is same! } 7... Bg7
{ 7...Bh6  is a funny idea of the comp. But our plans do not change after  8.Nd2 }
8. Nd2 O-O 9. Be2
{ We delay the development of the g1-knight for the time being as it gives rise to tactical shots with e4. }
9... Qe7 10. Qc2 { Protecting our bishop and getting ready for Nf3. } 10... f5
11. Ngf3 a5 12. Rc1
{ We continue wasting time and delaying castling since g5 ideas are annoying for us. }
12... Bd7 13. Qc5
{ 'We are going to the endgame now!' Any Marvel fans in the house?? Nobody?? }
13... Qe6 14. h4 { I like this move whenever it happens! } 14... h6 15. O-O
{ With a slight advantage for us as we have stopped g5 ideas for the time being. }
*

