[White "The Brave and The Bold: 1.b3 e5 2.Bb2 Nc6"]
[Black "4.e3 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.a3 g6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre with a false sense of security, only to take it all back with interest at the right time! }
1... e5
{ This is one of the most direct attempts and the most principled way to play against the Nimzo-Larsen.   1...Nc6  2.Bb2  will transpose. }
2. Bb2
{ The fight is already beginning. Black has to make a decision on how to defend the pawn. }
2... Nc6 3. c4
{ Inspired by Fischer's direction, we fight for the control of the central square on d5. }
3... Nf6
{ Continuing with development and Black is preparing to break with d5. } 4. e3
{ We open up the path of the f1-bishop while keeping our development schemes of the knight's hidden for the time being. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. a3
{ An important move restricting Black's ideas with Ndb4. } 6... g6
{ There are many who would prefer to do a kingside fianchetto...   Or  6...f6  we need not be bothered with this move as  7.b4  Be6  only leads to...  8.Nf3  with a transposition tothis variation after  8...Qd7  9.Qc2 }
7. d3 { Our concept is same! } 7... Bg7
{ 7...Bh6  is a funny idea of the comp. But our plans do not change after  8.Nd2 }
8. Nd2 O-O 9. Be2
{ We delay the development of the g1-knight for the time being as it gives rise to tactical shots with e4. }
9... Qe7 10. Qc2 { Protecting our bishop and getting ready for Nf3. } 10... f5
11. Ngf3 g5 12. h3 { Fighting against the pawn storm. } 12... g4
{ Black insists! } 13. hxg4 fxg4 14. Nh2 g3 15. Bf3
{ A nice way to deal with the gxf2+ ideas. } 15... gxf2+ 16. Ke2
{ With a funky position. } 16... Be6 17. Ne4
{ White's king is quite safe on e2 which is weird. 😀 } 17... Rad8 18. Raf1
{ Black has to be very careful not to end up worse. Let's have a look at some lines }
18... Bh6
{ Going for White's only weak point in his camp, the e3-pawn!   Comp's second best move is the interesting  18...Qe8  19.Rxf2  Ncb4!  20.axb4  Nxb4  if the Black queen was on  e7  , we could have played  Qc5  forcing the exchange. This was the point behind Black's strange retreat.  21.Qb1!  The safest square for the queen away from the attack of the knight.  21...Nxd3  22.Ba3  Rf7  23.Rd1!  The knight on  d3  is worth giving up the rook.  23...Nxf2  24.Kxf2  Rxd1  25.Qxd1  with a dynamically balanced middlegame where I am slightly leaning towards White due to the minor pieces and the potential to create play against the Black king. }
19. Ng4 Bg5
{ The natural  19...Bxg4  is met by  20.Rxh6!  After this, Black will find it hard to defend against White's attack and the b2-bishop will have the last laugh.  20...Bxf3  21.gxf3  Rxf3!  Making use of a cute tactical trick. If black does not take on  f3  , they lose without a fight.  22.Kxf3  Qf8+  23.Nf6  An epic intermediate check!  23...Nxf6  24.Rh3!  unfortunately for Black, the discovered check does not lead to anything as he can't target any of Black's pieces.  24...Rxd3!  White can't take on  d3  , due to the fork with e5-e4+.  25.Rg3+  Kf7  26.Kxf2  with a winning attack and the king will be safe on  g1  , while our counterpart lacks any safe haven. }
20. Bc1 { Protecting e3 with everything we have got! } 20... Nf4+
{ Thanks to the fork on d4, we can't take on f4.   The only other decent alternative for Black is  20...Bxg4  21.Bxg4  Nf4+  Using tactical motifs to target the weak position of our king.  22.Kxf2!  Walking into the line of fire without any hesitation!  22...Nxd3+  23.Kg1  Rxf1+  24.Kxf1  The knight on  e4  and bishop on  g4  are doing a fabulous job of controlling the key squares around the king. One sample line is  24...Nxc1  25.Qxc1  Rf8+  26.Bf3  Nd8  The best defence.  27.Nxg5  Qxg5  28.Qxc7  Restoring the material equality and a slight initiative for White due to the superior imbalance of bishop vs knight in an open position. }
21. Kxf2 Nxd3+ 22. Kg1
{ The king feels safe on g1 as he is guarded by the rooks firmly. Here we have another major branch, Black has two interesting directions. }
22... Qg7
{ 22...Bh4  is the alternative.  23.Nh6+  An important check to stop any h7-h5 ideas.  23...Kg7  24.b4!  We coolly improve our situation on the queenside.  24...Kxh6  25.g3  Pinning and winning!  25...Rg8  Black is copying our strategy, this is completely unacceptable!  26.Bg2  No more waiting and we will take on  h4  next #whateverittakes.  26...Rg6  27.Rxh4+  Kg7  28.Kh2  with a nice initiative as compensation for the pawn.   Black can also try @@StartFEN@@3r1r2/ppp1q1kp/2n1b2N/4p3/1P2N2b/P2nPB2/2Q3P1/2B2RKR b - - 0 24@@EndFEN@@  24...a6  we continue with  25.Bd2  with a complicated fight and if Black takes  25...Kxh6  26.Nc5  e4  Black's only chance.   Other alternatives include @@StartFEN@@3r1r2/1pp1q2p/p1n1b2k/2N1p3/1P5b/P2nPB2/2QB2P1/5RKR b - - 0 26@@EndFEN@@  26...Bc8  27.Nxd3  Kg7  28.Nc5  with a slightly better position due to the pressure along the h-file and more active pieces.   @@StartFEN@@3r1r2/1pp1q2p/p1n1b2k/2N1p3/1P5b/P2nPB2/2QB2P1/5RKR b - - 0 26@@EndFEN@@  26...Nxc5  is met by the stunning  27.Be1!!  Bf5  28.Bxh4  with a winning position thanks to the discovered attack along the h-file.  27.Nxe6  Now we are forcing in line...  27...exf3  28.Nxf8  Rxf8  29.Qxd3  f2+  30.Rxf2  Forced otherwise we run into a mate on  g3  .  30...Rxf2  31.Be1  Rf4!  A cool and only way to keep the balance.  32.exf4  Qxe1+  33.Kh2  Qe6  Only move again.  34.g3  Preparing  Kg2  and the h-file will become Black's major source of concern.  34...Bf6  35.Kg2+  Kg7  36.Rxh7+  Kf8  37.Rxc7  with a nice material imbalance of Rook + 2 pawns vs Bishop & Knight. }
23. Rh3 { Activating our rook and Black has only one way not to get worse. }
23... Kh8
{ Moving away from any danger along the g-file. I decided to give a long line which leads to an endgame by force.   The typical exchange with  23...Bxg4  24.Bxg4  Rxf1+  25.Kxf1  gives White a clear advantage thanks to the attack which will come along the light squares. }
24. Rd1 { The beginning of the end... } 24... Nxc1 25. Nxg5 Rxd1+ 26. Bxd1 Bf5
{ The best way to defend against the attack on h7.   The lame  26...Bg8  would be met with  27.Nxh7!  Bxh7  28.Qxc1  with a winning advantage due to the lack of protection for the Black king. }
27. e4 Qxg5 28. exf5 Nd4 29. Qxc7 Nce2+ 30. Bxe2 Nxe2+ 31. Kf2
{ Our king deserves to be praised for his bravery in this line. } 31... Qxf5+
32. Rf3 Nf4 { Forced. } 33. Qxe5+ Qxe5 34. Nxe5
{ Once the dust has cleared, all is well for both sides. } 34... Kg7 35. b4
{ With an equal endgame. } *

