1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre with a false sense of security, only to take it all back with interest at the right time! }
1... e5
{ This is one of the most direct attempts and the most principled way to play against the Nimzo-Larsen.   1...Nc6  2.Bb2  will transpose. }
2. Bb2
{ The fight is already beginning. Black has to make a decision on how to defend the pawn. }
2... Nc6 3. c4
{ Inspired by Fischer's direction, we fight for the control of the central square on d5. }
3... Nf6
{ Continuing with development and Black is preparing to break with d5. } 4. e3
{ We open up the path of the f1-bishop while keeping our development schemes of the knight's hidden for the time being. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. a3
{ An important move restricting Black's ideas with Ndb4. } 6... Be7
{ The second most popular line is this very soft move. I think it is popular simply because Black is trying to play like the Sicilian defence reversed where the bishop is reasonably well placed on e2, but here this is definitely not the case! }
7. Qc2
{ The best square for the queen, since it is in line with our concept of a3 which prevents Nb4 ideas and facilitates the safe house for the queen on c2 where it keeps an eye on e4 ideas for black, at the same time has pressure along c-file. }
7... O-O 8. Nf3
{ In the Be7 line, we delay d3 for one more move to have the Bd3 idea ready. }
8... Bd6 9. Bd3 { One of the advantages of delaying d3. } 9... h6 10. Nc3
{ With a pleasant game ahead thanks to our monster bishops. } *

