1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, a false sense of security... Only to take all of them back with interest at the right time! }
1... e5
{ After  1...d6  2.Bb2  Black is well advised to transpose to 1...e5 territory! }
2. Bb2 d6 3. c4
{ I feel this is the most critical attempt, but for some reason, it is only the 3rd most popular move after e3 and g3!   This is less commital as we keep all options involving both e3 and g3 ideas open. }
3... f5 4. e3
{ 4.d4  is also possible and will most likely transpose to our line. } 4... Nf6
5. d4 e4
{ This opens up a couple of weaknesses on f4 and g5 for our g1-knight. } 6. Nc3
g6 7. Nh3 { The knight is heading to its destined outpost on f4. } 7... Bg7
{ After  7...c6  we play  8.d5!  of course, we can never allow Black to achieve d5 himself  8...c5  9.Nf4  followed by Be2 and h4 with a clear advantage. }
8. Nf4 O-O 9. h4
{ With a clear advantage as we can go for long castling and follow it up with a kingside attack.   I ran into this line in some bullet games... So I felt obliged to add it. }
9... c6 10. h5 { Bringing the fight to h-file and the rook! } 10... g5 11. h6
Bh8 12. Nh3 { This is stronger than Nh5. } 12... Ng4 13. Qd2
{ Time to prepare long castling. } 13... Nxh6 14. f4
{ Giving Black 3 equally horrible choices:   1. Take on f3 and get mated on the g-file.   2. Take on f4 and get mated on the h-file.   3. Play g4 and allow the knight to come to g5 and possibly still get mated on the h-file. }
14... g4 15. Ng5 Bg7 16. d5
{ With a winning attack along the h-file since Black's defences will fall apart after the exchange of the dark-squared bishop. }
