[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Brave and The Bold: 1.b3 e5 2.Bb2 d6 & Other Jokes"]
[Black "2.Bb2 d6 3.c4 Nd7 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, a false sense of security... Only to take all of them back with interest at the right time! }
1... e5
{ After  1...d6  2.Bb2  Black is well advised to transpose to 1...e5 territory! }
2. Bb2 d6 3. c4
{ I feel this is the most critical attempt, but for some reason, it is only the 3rd most popular move after e3 and g3!   This is less commital as we keep all options involving both e3 and g3 ideas open. }
3... Nd7 4. e3 { Preparing d4. } 4... g6 5. d4 Bg7 6. dxe5
{ As a rule, many times we tend to clarify the tension in the center to give specific tasks and locations for our minor pieces. }
6... Nxe5
{ Or  6...dxe5  Nakamura - Carlsen, Speed Chess 2018.  7.Nf3!  we transpose to 3... g6, which we've examinedhere. }
7. Nc3 Nf6 8. Be2
{ So that after Nf3 Nxf3 we can take back with the bishop controlling the h1-a8 diagonal. }
8... O-O 9. Nf3 Ne4 { A nice tactical shot. } 10. Rc1
{ We just ignore the beauty... } 10... Nxf3+ 11. Bxf3 Nc5
{ Exchanging on c3 was in our favour. } 12. O-O Bf5 13. Qd2 Re8 14. Rcd1
{ The rook wasn't doing anything on c1 anymore! } 14... a5 15. Nb5
{ With a slight edge for White in Ionescu - Grigore, 1999. As a rule, it is good for us to exchange the dark-squared bishop to weaken's Black kingside. }
*

