[Black "2.Bb2 d6 3.c4 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, a false sense of security... Only to take all of them back with interest at the right time! }
1... e5
{ After  1...d6  2.Bb2  Black is well advised to transpose to 1...e5 territory! }
2. Bb2 d6 3. c4
{ I feel this is the most critical attempt, but for some reason, it is only the 3rd most popular move after e3 and g3!   This is less commital as we keep all options involving both e3 and g3 ideas open. }
3... Nf6 4. Nc3 { We keep our kingside development plans hidden. } 4... c6 5.
d4
{ Now that the c6-square is not available to the knight, the center break gains in strength. }
5... Be7
{ Or  5...exd4  6.Qxd4  with a slight advantage, thanks to the presence of a pawn on c6... The queen will reign supreme on d4. }
6. e3
{ We stabilize the centre and then continue with our evil plans of world domination. 😀 }
6... O-O 7. Nge2
{ Black could try to find a different way for the b8-knight with... } 7... Na6
8. a3 { As usual we are restricting the knight. } 8... Re8 9. h3
{ This a3 and h3 make a nice symmetry and it is easy to remember! } 9... Bf5
{ After  9...Bf8  10.Qc2  e4  Black is threatening to fix the pawn structure with d5...  11.d5!  With a good position due to some play on the kingside later on in the game! }
10. g4
{ Kicking the bishop with tempo and gaining more control and space on the kingside. }
10... Bg6 11. Bg2
{ With a very nice position and we are controlling the entire board! } *

