1... b6 { Black doesn't want to think on his own, and instead just copies us! }
2. e4
{ We muddle up Black's lazy plans. The alternative  2.Bb2  Bb7  seems quite easy for Black and frankly, not very challenging. }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3 c5 4. d4 { Yeah baby! } 4... cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6
{ At some point, Black has to play this to kick the queen out of her dominating position. }
6. Qd2 { The best place for the queen. } 6... Nf6 7. Bb2
{ With a good position for White. Similar positions will arise in the following chapters for those who want more context : }
7... e6 8. O-O-O Bb4 { 8...Bc5  would transpose after  9.f3  O-O  here. } 9. f3
{ Supporting e4 and preparing g4 ideas. } 9... Qe7 10. Kb1 O-O 11. Nge2 Rfd8
12. Qc1 { A brilliant way to break the pin and reduce the power of d5 ideas. }
12... Rac8 13. g4
{ With advantage due to the attacking possibilites on the kingside. } *

