1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, a false sense of security... Only to take all of them back with interest at the right time! }
1... b6 { Black doesn't want to think on his own, and instead just copies us! }
2. e4
{ We muddle up Black's lazy plans. The alternative  2.Bb2  Bb7  seems quite easy for Black and frankly, not very challenging. }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bc4 Bc5
{ It is worth mentioning that  5...Nf6  is simply lost after  6.Ng5! } 6. O-O
Nf6 7. d3 O-O 8. Bg5
{ We wreak havoc on the light squares, with a solid advantage.   For example, if Black goes  8...Be7  then  9.Re1  developing the rook and preparing the d4-break.  9...d6  10.d4  Now we are the boss in the center!  10...h6  11.Bh4  with a slight pull thanks to the space, center control and more actively placed pieces. We can follow it up with a4-d5 ideas.   If Black goes for  8...h6  instead, we can simply play  9.Bxf6!  as the control of the light squares is more important than the bishop pair here.  9...Qxf6  10.Nd5  Qd8  11.c3  preparing for b4/d4 ideas.  11...a5  12.Re1  followed by d3-d4 next with a nice advantage due to the central control and strong knight on  d5  . }
*

