[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Perfect Symmetry: The Double Fianchetto"]
[Black "5.Bg2 b6 6.c4 c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, a false sense of security...Only to take all of them back with interest at the right time! }
1... Nf6
{ As seen in the previous chapter,  1...b6  is not the best way as we strike with  2.e4! }
2. Bb2 g6
{ 'Two can play this game!'  2...b6  was shownhere in the previous chapter and leads to a transposition. }
3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3
{ We just take it one step further and aim for a double fianchetto! } 4... O-O
5. Bg2
{ This is a major tabiya, and there are many ways for Black to continue here. In this chapter, we focus on the lines with ...b6. }
5... b6 6. c4
{ Adding a slight twist! No matter how badly Black wants it, he won't be able to fully copy us.  6.O-O  Bb7  7.c4  c5  8.d4  d5!  Black fulfils his life's purpose by staying true to his way till the end. 😀 I feel he has completely equalized here. }
6... c5 7. d4 { Getting in d4 when Black can't take it! } 7... e6 8. O-O Bb7 9.
Nc3 { With nice play in the centre. } *

