4. Bxf6
{ Usually we don't exchange this bishop for a knight, but here Black was really asking for it. }
4... exf6 5. Nc3
{ This is one of the main points behind Bxf6: we are in time to stop d5 from Black. }
5... Bg7 6. g3
{ Our play is very easy and straightforward with play on the light squares along the long diagonal. }
6... O-O 7. Bg2 f5 { Activating his own bishop. } 8. Rc1
{ A useful move to prevent any Bxc3 ideas. } 8... c6 9. e3
{ Black will have to play Nd7 at some point and transpose to the mainlines. } *

