1... g6 { Two can play this game! Fighting fire with fire! } 2. Bb2 Nf6 3. Nf3
Bg7 4. g3 { We just take it one step further and aim for a double fianchetto! }
4... O-O 5. Bg2
{ This is a major tabiya, and there are many ways for Black to continue here... But the true King's Indian player can play only the following move! }
5... d6 6. d4 a5 { One of the best replies for Black. } 7. O-O a4 8. b4
{ I like this slightly different path... Also, as a rule, we can always remember that a5-a4 ideas have to be met with b4! }
8... d5 9. a3 Nbd7 10. c4
{ I like this fresh direction, giving up the c4-pawn in order to take control of the center with e4.  As previously seen, if we are not alert and continue with  10.Nbd2  Black could create a lockdown with  10...b5!?  11.Ne5  Nb6  12.e4  Nxe4  13.Nxe4  dxe4  14.Bxe4  Be6!  =∞ with full compensation if we decide to be greedy and take on a8. }
10... dxc4 11. Qc2
{ Attacking c4 and preparing e4. This is also the best place for the queen in this line, most of the time. }
11... Nb6 12. Nbd2 c6 13. e4
{ With full control over the centre and we can win back the c4-pawn with leisure. }
