Bg7 4. g3 { We just take it one step further and aim for a double fianchetto! }
4... O-O 5. Bg2
{ This is a major tabiya, and there are many ways for Black to continue here... But the true King's Indian player can play only the following move! }
5... d6 6. d4 Nc6
{ Black is trying to get in e5... but as usual, we welcome this advance with open arms! }
7. O-O e5 8. dxe5 Ng4 9. Qc1
{ This square ideal for the queen as it frees the d1-file for the rook, protects the bishop on b2 and keeps a watch on the dark squares. }
9... dxe5 10. Rd1 Bd7 11. h3 { Kicking the knight to the corner of the board! }
11... Nh6 12. Qd2 { The return of the queen to the d-file. } 12... Be6 13. Ng5
{ With a big advantage due to the potential outpost on d5 for the b1-knight and the issue of where to put the e6-bishop. }
