1... g6 { Two can play this game! Fighting fire with fire! } 2. Bb2 Nf6 3. Nf3
Bg7 4. g3 { We just take it one step further and aim for a double fianchetto! }
4... O-O 5. Bg2
{ This is a major tabiya, and there are many ways for Black to continue here... But the true King's Indian player can play only the following move! }
5... d6 6. d4 Nbd7 7. O-O
{ White's play is very easy and he has lots of plans with simple ideas, One way is to play a4-a5 to gain space and restrict Black's forces and also c4-Nc3 with good control over the centre. }
7... e5
{ This is the move I have faced most of the time... which just gives White the advantage without any effort! 😀 }
8. dxe5 Ng4 9. Qd2
{ The queen is well placed and prepares for action to be undertaken after Black recaptures on e5. }
9... dxe5 10. h3 Nh6 11. a4
{ Since Black is more or less obilged to play c6... White prepares a4-a5 which will put Black in an uncomfortable spot to allow either a6 ideas or play a6 himself, but permanently weakening b6 and c5 in the process. }
11... f6 12. Rd1 Nf7 13. a5
{ With a clear advantage due to threats like a6 and mastery of the d-file. } *

