[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, a false sense of security... Only to take all of them back with interest at the right time! }
1... Nf6 2. Bb2 g6 { 'Two can play this game!' } 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3
{ We just take it one step further and aim for a double fianchetto! } 4... O-O
5. Bg2
{ This is a major tabiya, there are many ways for Black to continue here. }
5... d5 6. c4
{ Attacking the centre before Black can comfortably stabilize it. } 6... c6
{ It's like Black is saying 'I am a very solid player!'... Nimzo-Larsen players would reply 'We don't care!' }
7. O-O { One prophylactic and futuristic noob went for } 7... Re8
{ which is surprisingly quite popular! } 8. d4 Bf5 9. e3
{ The typical move to support the center and clear the e2-square for queen. }
9... Nbd7 10. Qe2 { What we say...we do! } 10... dxc4
{ Black gives away the tension in the center in order to prepare a nasty break! }
11. Qxc4 e5 { This thrust was his point. } 12. dxe5 Ng4 13. e6
{ Only way otherwise we could easily end up worse if we allow a knight to come to e5. }
13... Bxe6
{ The bishop also has lost his control over the d3 square which works in our favour. }
14. Qe2 Bxb2 15. Qxb2
{ with a slightly more pleasant middlegame due to the outpost on d4 for the knight and the central pawn majority. }
