e4 { followed by strong play using the fianchettoed bishops. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The English Way: 1.b3 c5 2.Bb2 Nc6"]
[Black "3.c4 Nf6 4.e3 e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre with a false sense of security, only to take it all back with interest at the right time! }
1... c5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. c4
{ The move order is very important, we delay Nf3 for the time being. } 3... Nf6
4. e3
{ 4.Bxf6  gxf6  5.Nc3  with a strategical fight. To be honest, I wouldn't mind trying this as White!  5...e6  6.e3  with a pleasant advantage.   5...h5!  Black has to do this, otherwise he gets slightly worse.  6.h4!  Fixing the pawn on h5 and making it a future target for our pieces.  6...d6  7.g3  with nice play on the light squares. }
4... e5
{ Or  4...g6  5.Bxf6!  Now that Black is mixing c5 and g6 ideas, the d5-square is up for grabs 😀.   5...exf6  6.Nc3  with advantage due to the beautiful square on d5 which can be used as an outpost for the knights and bishop! }
5. Nf3 { Starting the assault on the centre. } 5... e4
{ Black can also try the passive  5...d6  6.d3  g6  7.g3  Double fianchetto is the path to heaven!  7...Bg7  8.Bg2  O-O  9.O-O  We have a nice version of the English symmetry, since the knight on  f6  is misplaced.  9...h6  10.Nc3  Be6  11.Rc1  with a nice edge and we can play for two breaks  d4  or  b4  . }
6. Ne5 h5
{ Gaining some space on the kingside and stopping Ng4 ideas.   Black has two alternatives here: Firstly,  6...Bd6  7.Ng4  is simply bad for Black.   @@StartFEN@@ r1bqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/2n2n2/2p1N3/2P1p3/1P2P3/PB1P1PPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@ and Secondly,  6...Qe7  7.f4  Supporting the knight, leaving Black with the unpleasant choice between allowing a stronghold on  e5  or opening the f-file with  7...exf3  8.Nxf3  Whenever we achieve the f4-break successfully...The Nimzo-Larsen masters would be proud of us! }
7. d3 { with a slightly more comfortable position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The English Way: 1.b3 c5 2.Bb2 Nc6"]
[Black "4.e3 e6 5.Nf3 b6 6.g3 d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre with a false sense of security, only to take it all back with interest at the right time! }
1... c5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. c4
{ The move order is very important, we delay Nf3 for the time being. } 3... Nf6
4. e3 { One of the toughest lines I had to fight against was the solid } 4...
e6 5. Nf3
{ After  5...d5  6.cxd5  either recapture will lead to the QGD chapter. } 5...
b6
{ This is slightly different than 4...b6 as we have already committed the knight to f3. }
6. g3 { If Black strikes in the centre with } 6... d5 7. Bg2
{ The fabulous double fianchetto in action! } 7... Ba6
{ I don't really know if the bishop is better placed on a6! } 8. O-O
{ Worse is } 8... dxc4 9. bxc4 { Already we have a big advantage! } 9... Bxc4
{ Otherwise there was no point in taking on c4 😀 } 10. d3
{ This is not easy to find unless you know it 😀. } 10... Qxd3 11. Nfd2
{ A very nice discovered attack! } 11... Rc8 12. Re1
{ Preparing the nasty Bf1 winning the c4-bishop. } 12... b5
{ Only move which doesn't lose immediately  12...Bd5  13.e4  wins a piece. }
13. a4 { Breaking the support of c4-bishop. } 13... a6 14. Bxf6
{ Time to be greedy and get back what we have sacrificed! } 14... gxf6 15.
Bxc6+ Rxc6 16. Qf3
{ with a clear advantage thanks to weak king @@StartBracket@@side@@EndBracket@@ and the underdeveloped pieces. }
