1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre with a false sense of security, only to take it all back with interest at the right time! }
1... c5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. c4
{ The move order is very important, we delay Nf3 for the time being. } 3... Nf6
4. e3 { One of the toughest lines I had to fight against was the solid } 4...
e6 5. Nf3
{ After  5...d5  6.cxd5  either recapture will lead to the QGD chapter. } 5...
b6
{ This is slightly different than 4...b6 as we have already committed the knight to f3. }
6. g3 { Typical and our preferred way to develop the bishop 😀. } 6... Be7
{ Black first decides to finish his kingside development and then figure out where to put the c8-bishop. }
7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O d5
{ Black is still biding his time and not commiting his bishop. } 9. Nc3 Bb7
{ 9...Ba6  looks weird and pointless after  10.d3  What is the bishop doing on a6? }
10. cxd5
{ Asking Black to make a decision which could affect the path of both of our lives... }
10... Nxd5 11. Nxd5
{ As a rule the structure after  10...exd5  11.d4  is advantageous for us due to the potential pressure we can exert on the center. }
11... Qxd5 12. d4
{ Let's have a look at some natural rook moves starting with } 12... Rfd8 13.
Ne5 Qd6 14. Qf3
{ Utilising the recently weakened f7 pawn and the pressure along the h1-a8 diagonal. }
14... Nxe5 15. Qxb7 Nd3 16. Ba3
{ with a clear advantage due to the powerful bishop pair. } *

