{ But we are not done yet!! Not today not ever... } 18... g5
{ only move again 😀. } 19. hxg5 Qg7 20. e5
{ Thanks to the continuous tempi attack on the queen, we have managed to secure a safe return for the brave knight on d7! }
20... Kh8
{ Black is also not going to make things so easy for us.   20...Nxe5  21.Bb2  is just bad for Black. }
21. Bf4 { Threatening to play Rc1. } 21... Bxg5 22. Qh5
{ If Black tries to keep the exchange with } 22... Rg8 23. Bxg5
{ 'We are going to the endgame now!' } 23... Qxg5 24. Qxg5 Rxg5 25. Rfd1
{ e5 is tactically defended. } 25... Kg7
{ The following line is kind of forced for both sides, so I decided to give some more moves! }
26. Rac1 Nb8
{ After  26...Na5  27.b4  and Black suffers huge material losses. } 27. Nf6
{ The only way to keep the fight going! } 27... Rxd1+ 28. Rxd1 Bxg2 29. f4
{ Protecting e5 is the priority, which in turn makes the knight on f6, a complete monster! }
29... Bf3 { 29...Rxg3  30.Nh5+  loses the rook and the game. } 30. Rd8
{ Going for the gold! } 30... Rxg3+ 31. Kf2 Rg6
{ Once again, the only way not to lose.   If Black tries to keep the bishop with  31...Rh3  32.Rg8+  Kh6  33.Rg5!  followed by mate in 4 due to Ng8, since Black will go into self destruct mode by giving his pieces to stop it. 😀. }
32. Kxf3 Na6
{ After  32...Nc6  33.Rd1  White has full compensation and an ongoing attack that continues to the endgame... thanks to the knight on f6!  The other passive way allows }
33. Ne8+ Kh6
{ Or  33...Kf8  34.Ra8  with a winning advantage thanks to the superior major and minor piece! }
34. Rd1 { with mating attack or give the rook dilemma 😀. } *

