{ As a rule the structure after  10...exd5  11.d4  is advantageous for us due to the potential pressure we can exert on the center. }
11... Qxd5 12. d4 { One of the most natural moves would be } 12... Rad8 13. Ne5
{ Discovered attack from the bishop and suddenly the mighty queen starts to feel not so happy on d5. }
13... Qd6 14. dxc5 Qxc5 { Black has to walk on a thin line to survive this. }
15. Nd7 { No guts no glory! } 15... Qf5 16. e4 Qg5
{ Only move! After  16...Qg6  we can escape the pin on the d-file with  17.Nxf8  also attacking Black's queen. }
17. h4 Qh6 { The only safehouse for the queen. } 18. Bc1
{ But we are not done yet!! Not today not ever... } 18... g5
{ only move again 😀. } 19. hxg5 Qg7 20. e5
{ Thanks to the continuous tempi attack on the queen, we have managed to secure a safe return for the brave knight on d7! }
20... Kh8
{ Black is also not going to make things so easy for us.   20...Nxe5  21.Bb2  is just bad for Black. }
21. Bf4 { Threatening to play Rc1. } 21... Bxg5 22. Qh5
{ An improvement over the existing games and books! After  22.Bxg5  Qxg5  I feel that Black is fine here, for instance,  23.Nxf8  Rxd1  24.Raxd1  h5!  with equality in Satici-Martello email 2011. }
22... Bxf4 23. Nxf8 { Exchange operation successful! } 23... Rxf8 24. gxf4
{ Also leading to same is } 24... Nxe5 25. Qg5 Rg8
{ Transposes to our main variation here. } *

