6... O-O 7. Be2 d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5
{ 8...exd5  9.d4  would transpose to @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1pbppp/2n1pn2/2p5/2P5/1PN1PN2/PB1P1PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d5  which we have examinedhere. }
9. Qc2
{ Giving the position a similar touch like in our QGD chapter with the only difference is that we have already commited Be2. }
9... b6 10. h4
{ This becomes a typical thrust whenever there is no knight on f6 which in turn allows Ng5 ideas. }
10... Ncb4 11. Qb1 { Continuing to prepare Ng5. } 11... f5
{ Best way to fight against Ng5 ideas. } 12. a3 { GO BACK SIMON! } 12... Nxc3
13. Bxc3 Nc6 14. b4
{ Achieving this break is really a good sign and with this we cement our clear advantage. }
14... cxb4 15. axb4 a5
{ Black doesn't have to allow b5 which would fix the a7-pawn. } 16. bxa5 bxa5
17. O-O
{ We are happy to give our h4-pawn in order to make sure that our nimzo-larsen bishop will have no match! }
17... Bxh4 18. Rc1 { Threatening Bg7 ideas with advantage. } *

