[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The English Way: 1.b3 c5 2.Bb2 Nc6"]
[Black "4.e3 b6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre with a false sense of security, only to take it all back with interest at the right time! }
1... c5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. c4
{ The move order is very important, we delay Nf3 for the time being. } 3... Nf6
4. e3
{ 4.Bxf6  gxf6  5.Nc3  with a strategical fight. To be honest I wouldn't mind trying this as White!  5...e6  6.e3  with a pleasant advantage.   5...h5!  Black has to do this, otherwise he gets slightly worse.  6.h4!  Fixing the pawn on h5 and making it a future target for our pieces.  6...d6  7.g3  with play on the light squares. }
4... b6 5. g3 { We have to insist on the fianchetto at any cost! } 5... Bb7 6.
Bxf6
{ The time was ripe for our brave bishop to perish in order to ensure that the light squares will be ruled by us. }
6... gxf6 7. Bg2 h5
{ Black has to take drastic measures in order to fight against our light square and structural dominance. }
8. h4
{ Fixing the pawn on h5 and it will become a future target of our minor pieces. }
8... d5 { The force is strong with this one! } 9. cxd5
{ 9.Bxd5  is not as effective as  9...Qd7  gives Black full compensation for the pawn. }
9... Nb4 10. Nc3 { Catching up in development. } 10... Nxd5 11. Nxd5
{ Making sure that the remaining bishop on f8 will only be a spectator in the light saber fight. }
11... Bxd5 12. Nf3 e5 13. O-O
{ with a slightly better middlegame thanks to our future play on the light squares. }
*

