[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre with a false sense of security, only to take it all back with interest at the right time! }
1... d5 2. Bb2 { Some have recommended } 2... c6
{ We can also reach this position via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.b3  c6  2.Bb2  d5 }
3. d3 { We stay adamant about our direction! } 3... Bf5 4. Nd2
{ e4 is coming! } 4... Nf6 5. g3 Nbd7
{ This is the only way to force us to play Ngf3 as otherwise Black will play e5 which is not ideal, if not for Nbd7, White can delay playing Ngf3 and continue normally with Bg2 followed by e4. }
6. Ngf3
{ As Naka would say 'It is what it is'...But early Nbd7 is not good for Black as we are in time to achieve e4. }
6... h6 7. Bg2 e6 8. O-O Bh7 9. e4
{ White has achieved a 100% score here! Hence Black is well advised to avoid this. }
9... dxe4 10. dxe4 Nxe4 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Re1
{ If Black retreats with the bishop } 12... Bg6
{ 12...Bh7  13.Nd4  with a very strong attack and if Black tries to finish development with  13...Be7  14.Qg4!  and White has way too many threats on the kingside and e-file. }
13. Nd4 { Threatening to take on e6! } 13... Be7
{ 13...Nf6  14.Nxc6!  A nice shot capitalising on the superior bishops and better development.  14...Qxd1  15.Raxd1  Bxc2  16.Rc1  Bh7  17.Ne5  with a clear advantage. Two sample lines are  17...Rb8  18.Bxb7!  Bolt from the Blue!  18...Rxb7  19.Rc8+  Ke7  20.Ba3+  Rb4  21.Bxb4#  A cool mating pattern. @@StartFEN@@ r3kb1r/pp3ppb/4pn1p/4N3/8/1P4P1/PB3PBP/2R1R1K1 b kq - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Bb4  18.Bxb7!  with a clear advantage due to the queenside pawn majority and superior minor and major pieces. }
14. Rxe6 { Beautiful sacrifice! } 14... fxe6 15. Nxe6
{ The knight and the bishop on b2 makes for a dangerous combo! } 15... Qc8 16.
Nxg7+ Kf7
{ 16...Kd8  17.Ne6+  Ke8  18.Bxh8  Winning the material back with two extra pawns and if Black tries to be greedy with  18...Kf7  then  19.Bc3  Kxe6  20.Bh3+  And the mighty bishop pair rules the board!  20...Bf5  21.Qe2+  The bishop on  f5  falls giving us a winning attack. }
17. Bh3 Bf6 18. Bxd7 Qd8
{ 18...Qb8  19.Be6+!  The queen is coming to  d7!  19...Kxg7  20.Qd7+  forcing the king to lose the support for the f6-bishop.  20...Kf8  21.Bxf6  with a winning advantage. }
19. Ne6 Qa5 20. Qf3
{ With a winning advantage due to the weak king and the ongoing attack. } *

