1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, a false sense of security... Only to take all of them back with interest at the right time! }
1... d5 2. Bb2 Bg4
{ was the preference of my childhood hero-Mikhal Tal. Black is cutting into White's plans of development. }
3. f3
{ We answer in style! One of the hidden advantages of not commiting Nf3! Attacking the bishop and clearing the path for e4. }
3... Bh5 4. h4
{ Nepo is fighting a lonely battle in this line...Let's also join in on the fun! }
4... f6 { This is the move I faced most in my bullet run. } 5. d4 c5 6. e4
{ Blasting open the centre to utilize Black's weaknesses on e6 and f7. } 6...
dxe4 7. g4
{ Kicking the bishop from the diagonal in order to falicitate fe4 ideas. } 7...
Bf7 8. d5 { What a move! Throwing in one pawn for activating our forces! } 8...
Qxd5 9. Qxd5 Bxd5 10. Nc3 Bc6 11. fxe4
{ White has full compensation for the pawn and some sample lines are } 11...
Na6 12. g5 { Opening up the h3-c8 diagonal. } 12... O-O-O 13. Bh3+ Kb8 14. Rd1
{ Exchanging the only active piece in Black's camp. } 14... Rxd1+ 15. Kxd1
{ Black is still struggling to finish his development, while we can get our knight to f4 or d5. }
