[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ozmin Attack: 1.b3 d5 2.Bb2 c5"]
[Black "4.Nf3 g6 5.Bb5+ Nbd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, a false sense of security... Only to take all of them back with interest at the right time! }
1... d5 2. Bb2 c5
{ Black starts the fight for the centre. I came up with the name Ozmin Attack @@StartBracket@@which is just Nimzo put in reverse order@@EndBracket@@ thanks to the help of my discord members 😀. }
3. e3
{ The bishop is usually best placed on b5 in order to fight for the control of the e5-square. }
3... Nf6 { Black can try to be flexible with his plans. } 4. Nf3
{ Compared to the other fianchetto systems with Nf6-g6, here Black has commited a serious felony and captured the center without our permission! }
4... g6 5. Bb5+
{ This line unbalances a lot of things from the get go. It seems to be the perfect test for Black as White is statically a lot better. }
5... Nbd7
{ We have forced the knight to d7 where it doesn't control the central squares. }
6. O-O
{ Before we start the chaos, it always makes good sense to finish castling 😀. }
6... Bg7 7. c4 { The real fight for the centre begins after this move. } 7...
dxc4 8. bxc4 { Creating an imbalance in the spirit of our masters! } 8... a6 9.
Ba4 { Of course we are not giving our bishop anymore! } 9... O-O 10. Nc3
{ As we have learnt, fianchetto is the best way to activate the bishops :  , one of the best options for Black is }
10... b6
{ Another option is  10...Nb6  11.Bb3!  Temporarily dimming the bishop in order to protect  c4  .  11...Bf5  12.d4  Here we welcome the hanging pawns with open arms due to the misplaced knight on  b6  and lack of pressure from Black.  12...Rc8  13.Qe2  with a fight in the center. }
11. Qe2
{ Since we have played e3, this square looks more appealing for the queen. }
11... Bb7 12. d3
{ We don't commit d4 as that will give Black the chance to target our center due to the possible creation of hanging pawns. }
12... Qc7 13. Rab1 { The tempting knight jump with } 13... Ng4 { runs into }
14. e4 { with idea to play Nd5 next. } 14... e6 { Black intends to play Nde5. }
15. Bxd7
{ Of course we cannot allow a knight to e5 which will help cement Black's control of the d4 square. }
15... Qxd7 16. h3 { Time to take back what is rightfully ours! } 16... Ne5 17.
Nxe5 Bxe5 18. Nd5
{ A brilliant shot utlizing the weakness on b6 and loosely placed bishop on e5. }
18... exd5
{ 18...Bxb2  just loses a pawn to  19.Nxb6!  Double attack!  19...Qe7  20.Qxb2  with a healthy extra pawn and clear advantage. }
19. Bxe5
{ Black's demise will happen on the dark squares due to his missing link on g7. }
*

