[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ozmin Attack: 1.b3 d5 2.Bb2 c5"]
[Black "5.Nf3 Nf6 6.c4 a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ We just give Black the centre, a false sense of security... Only to take all of them back with interest at the right time! }
1... d5 2. Bb2 c5
{ Black starts the fight for the centre. I came up with the name Ozmin Attack @@StartBracket@@which is just Nimzo put in reverse order@@EndBracket@@ thanks to the help of my discord members 😀. }
3. e3
{ The bishop is usually best placed on b5 in order to fight for the control of the e5-square. }
3... Nc6 4. Bb5
{ Given a choice,we always go for this placement for the bishop as it helps us fight for the e5-square. }
4... Bd7 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. c4
{ We strike the centre before Black is fully ready!   An alternative is  6.O-O  g6!  wasn't so easy to crack and I felt play wasn't so challenging for Black.  7.Nc3   7.Bxf6  is not very promising because of  exf6  8.Nc3  a6!  Forcing us to take on  c6  or to relax the pressure on the a4-e8 diagonal.  9.Bxc6  Bxc6  with slight advantage to Black!  7...a6!  We are forced to give up our beautiful pair.  8.Bxc6  Bxc6  9.d4!  could be another way to play. }
6... a6 7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. Ne5 { Making sure we win back the bishop. } 8... Rc8
{ Otherwise we will force the hideous doubled pawn with Nxc6. } 9. O-O e6
{ Here since we have already commited c4...it doesn't go so well with f4 ideas. }
10. d3
{ It is important not to allow play and to aim for play on the light squares in order to compensate for the absence of our bishop who perished bravely with the hope that we will win the battle 😀. }
10... Be7 11. Nxc6 { The time had come... } 11... Rxc6 12. Qe2
{ Winter is coming! } 12... O-O 13. e4
{ A nice improvement starting the space gain.   13.Nd2  was seen before, but it is too slow }
13... Nd7
{ If  13...b5  then  14.Nd2  with play on the centre and kingside.   The natural  13...dxe4  would give a big advantage for us after  14.dxe4  Nd7  15.e5!  The pawn is really a thorn in Black's position as it dictates the future course of the game where we will put the knight on  e4  giving rise to both Nd6/  Nf6  ideas. }
14. f4
{ Making our intentions very clear, we just have to bulldoze on the kingside! }
14... dxc4 15. dxc4 Nb8
{ The only way. Otherwise, Black is significantly worse. } 16. Nd2 Rd6
{ This was Black's brillant concept to fight against the bishop's influence. }
17. Rad1 Nc6 18. e5 Nd4
{ Black can also play the natural  18...Rd7  which allows  19.Ne4  Nd4  20.Qf2  and now we aim for the superior Q+N imbalance and the knight is well placed on  e4! }
19. Bxd4 { Getting our superior material imbalance of Q+N vs Q+B. } 19... Rxd4
20. Nf3 { The rook's joy on d4 was always going to be very short lived. } 20...
Rxd1 21. Rxd1 Qc7 22. g4
{ with a nice endgame and we can play on the light squares. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Queens Gambit Declined: 1.b3 d5 2.Bb2 Nf6-e6"]
[Black "1.b3 e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3 { Another decent move order is } 1... e6
{ Black is trying to stay flexible and confused at the same time. } 2. Bb2
{ Please take note that moving the f8-bishop would not end well for Black as the g7-pawn will be left hanging. }
2... c5
{ There is absolutely no point with this move order. Unless Black is a Sicilian player who is living in France and is a fan of The French Defense.     2...d5  will transposes to the QGD Chapter.   2...Nf6  transposes to another variant of QGD Chapter here   2...b6  3.e4  Capturing the center!  3...Bb7  4.Nc3  transposes to 'The Brave and The Copycat Chapter here. }
3. Nf3
{ I like this simple developing move and then deciding how to go on with our future...depending on Black's setup.   Another alternative move order with similar results is  3.e3  which will most likely transpose into  3.Nf3  lines. }
3... Nc6
{ 3...d5  4.e3  transposes to Ozmin Attack chapter here   3...Nf6  4.e3  d5  5.c4  transposes to QGD Chapter here }
4. e3 Nf6 { 4...d5  will transpose to Ozmin Attack chapter } 5. c4
{ Now we are in the 'English Way' Chapter } *

