[Result "*"]

1. b3 { Let's have a look at the delayed QGD line. } 1... Nf6 2. Bb2 e6
{ Black is not revealing what he wants to do in the centre yet and keeps the option of fianchetto with b6. }
3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 { Our favourite double-fianchetto! } 4... Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O
O-O
{ So far so good, both sides have finished their development and taken the king to safety. }
7. c4 d5 8. cxd5 { Before Black has a chance to take on c4. } 8... Nxd5 9. d4
{ Center capture : Done! } 9... Nd7 10. e4
{ I like this direct confrontation in the centre. } 10... N5f6 11. e5 Nd5
{ Black's threat is to break the centre with c5. } 12. h4
{ We create a hook on the kingside for gaining some play. } 12... a5
{ 12...h6  A useful prophylaxis against Nf3-g5 ideas.  13.Nbd2  The knight will go to  e4  or  c4  depending on the situation.  13...a5  Black is trying to do without  c5  in order to keep d6-square under check.  14.Nh2!  An innovative maneuver preparing to bring the knight to  g4  , where it will create lots of threats against the enemy king.   12...c5  can be met with  13.Na3!  with the idea of Na3-c4 eyeing the juicy d6-square. }
13. Nc3 { Fighting against a4 ideas. } 13... Nxc3 14. Bxc3 c5 15. Nd2
{ Exchanging the light-squared bishop and freeing the path for the knight to go to e4. }
15... Bxg2 16. Kxg2 cxd4 17. Bxd4
{ The bishop does both defensive and offensive roles in the center of the board. }
17... Nc5 18. Bxc5 { Leaving Black with a slightly weak minor piece. } 18...
Bxc5 19. Rc1 Qd5+ 20. Nf3
{ with an equal endgame where the knight seems to be more powerful than the bishop. }
