[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Queens Gambit Declined: 1.b3 d5 2.Bb2 Nf6-e6"]
[Black " 1.b3 Nf6 2.Bb2 e6 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3 { Let's have a look at the delayed QGD line. } 1... Nf6 2. Bb2 e6
{ Black is not revealing what he wants to do in the centre yet and keeps the option of fianchetto with b6. }
3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 { Our favourite double-fianchetto! } 4... Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O
O-O
{ So far so good, both sides have finished their development and taken the king to safety. }
7. c4 c5 8. d4 d5
{ This is very symmetrical except for the fact that we have an extra fianchetto! }
9. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Best way to aim for an equal game.  9...exd5  10.Nc3  with a slight advantage due to the pawn structure and the pressure we can exert on Black's pawns. If  9...Qxd5  then  10.Nc3  and White gains a tempo for free. }
10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Nbd2
{ Avoiding any exchanges for now and bringing the knight to e4. } 11... Nf6
{ 11...Nd7  12.Ne4  The knight looks nice on  e4  controlling key squares.  12...Be7  13.Qd4  A powerful centralisation of the queen!  13...N5f6  14.Ne5!  with a slightly more comfortable game due to the battery on the a1-h8 diagonal. }
12. Rc1
{ We have finished the development while Black needs some more moves to do it. }
12... Qe7
{ 12...Nbd7  13.Ng5!  Exchanging the bishop to target Black's c6-square.  13...Bxg2  14.Kxg2  and the knight will come to  e4  with small yet stable pressure. }
13. Ng5
{ This is a favourable exchange for us, in order to play on the light squares. }
13... Bxg2 14. Qc2
{ That's how you play Chess!! Threatening Bf6 and Qh7 mate. } 14... Nbd7 15.
Kxg2 { with a typical catalan type edge. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Queens Gambit Declined: 1.b3 d5 2.Bb2 Nf6-e6"]
[Black " 1.b3 Nf6 2.Bb2 e6 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3 { Let's have a look at the delayed QGD line. } 1... Nf6 2. Bb2 e6
{ Black is not revealing what he wants to do in the centre yet and keeps the option of fianchetto with b6. }
3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 { Our favourite double-fianchetto! } 4... Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O
O-O
{ So far so good, both sides have finished their development and taken the king to safety. }
7. c4 c5 8. d4 cxd4 9. Qxd4 Nc6 10. Qf4
{ The best place for the queen where it can pretend to be very active and also not get troubled by the minor pieces. }
10... d5
{ One funny way to exchange queens is  10...Qb8  11.Nc3!  Asking Black to take on  f4  and improve our central control  11...Qxf4  12.gxf4  with a better endgame due to the space and  Ne5  ideas. We keep the rooks on d1/c1 and follow it up with  e3  . }
11. Rd1 Qb8
{ 11...Qc8  12.Nbd2  with a slight pull as the Black is still figuring out where to hide from the pressure of the rooks.  Perhaps Black's best try in this position is   11...Qe8!  Moving away from the pin and keeping the queen in the only safe place where it can't be targeted by our forces.  12.Nc3  dxc4  13.Qxc4  Rd8  14.Qf4  We keep slight pressure due to the optical illusion of having better placed pieces. }
12. Ne5 { 'Into the fire!' } 12... Bd6
{ The other option  12...Nxe5  13.Bxe5  Qc8  14.Nd2  All set for the next phase!  14...dxc4  15.Nxc4  Bxg2  16.Kxg2  Qb7+  17.Qf3  Qxf3+  18.Kxf3  I would suggest you check out the two classics 'Reti-Karpov' 1980 and 'Anish Giri-Topalov' 2015 on how to play such type of positions. }
13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. Qe3
{ The bishop on b2 is our winning trump card which never fails to give us some hope throughout the entire line. }
14... Bc5 15. Qf3 Ne4 16. e3
{ with a slightly more comfortable game thanks to our more active pieces. } *

