[Result "*"]

1. b3 { Let's have a look at the delayed QGD line. } 1... Nf6 2. Bb2 e6
{ Black is not revealing what he wants to do in the centre yet and keeps the option of fianchetto with b6. }
3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 { Our favourite double-fianchetto! } 4... Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O
O-O
{ So far so good, both sides have finished their development and taken the king to safety. }
7. c4 c5 8. d4 cxd4 9. Qxd4 d6 10. Nc3
{ This is more actively placed than on d2. } 10... Nbd7 11. Rfd1
{ Threatening Nb5 and targetting the d6-pawn. } 11... a6
{ Black has got the hedgehog. } 12. e4
{ After this move there is no doubt who is the boss of the center! } 12... Qb8
{ Black is trying very hard to make b5 ideas work and in the process he is ignoring his rook on a8.   Black can also try  12...Qc7  13.Qe3!  Clearing the path for  Nd4  .  13...Rfe8  Rooks on  e8  and  c8  is the best files for them as they will be useful in preparing  d5  breaks.  14.Re1!  Only Popov went for this important relocation of the rooks.  14...Rac8  15.Rad1  The rooks are ideally placed against the central break with d6-d5.  15...Qb8  16.Nd4  with a space advantage and with careful preparation, we can start preparing for the kingside pawn storm.   Another option is  12...Rc8  13.Qe3  Nd4 is coming!  13...Qc7  14.Re1  N  followed by Rad1-Nd4 with strong control over the center and the entire position. }
13. Qe3
{ A necessary prophylactic retreat in order to facilitate Nd4 after which the b5 is well controlled by the two knights. }
13... Re8 14. Nd4 Bf8 { Winter is coming to d5 😀 } 15. Re1
{ This time only Yasser Seirawan has hit upon the right placement for the rooks! }
15... Qa7 { This looks so funny and silly 😀. } 16. Rad1 Rad8 17. h3
{ followed by Kh2-f4 and slowly advancing the kingside pawns. } *

