[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Queens Gambit Declined: 1.b3 d5 2.Bb2 Nf6-e6"]
[Black " 1.b3 d5 2.Bb2 Nf6 3.Nf3 e6  4.c4 c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Nf6 3. Nf3 e6 4. c4 c5 5. e3 dxc4
{ A funny sideline which a random dutch boy tweeted to me, begging me to check! }
6. Bxc4 a6
{ 6...Nc6  Developing the knight and hoping for d4 with a transposition to the Queens Gambit Accepted.  7.O-O  Be7  The bishop on e7 and the knight on c6 don't miss well with each other.  If Black tries   7...a6  8.Be2!  We refuse to transpose to the mainlines unless we are sure to get something concrete.  8...Be7  9.d4  with a better middlegame, after the eventual cd4 Nd4...our bishop can go to f3 and create pressure along the h1-a8 diagonal.  8.d4  8...cxd4  9.Nxd4  followed by Nd2 with a very pleasant edge thanks to the more active minor pieces and the queen has a nice spot on e2.   6...Be7  This is a lame way to play against us :@@EndBracket@@.  7.g4!  Of course! We don't need more incentive to play this and start the kingside assault.  7...O-O  8.g5  8...Nd5  9.Nc3  with good attacking chances on the kingside, due to the pawn on g5 and our main asset on b2 @@StartBracket@@Vachier-Ju Wenjun Gib 2019@@EndBracket@@. }
7. Rg1
{ A crazy and simple plan to play g4 next and gain the initiative on the kingside. }
7... Nc6
{ 7...h5  Comp's top choice, fighting against g4!  8.Be2!  A nice prophylactic retreat to play d3-Nbd2 next.  8...b6  9.d3  Keeping our pawn structure very flexible and hedgehog style!  9...Nc6  10.a3  Our usual move to stop any Nb4 disturbances.  10...Bb7  11.Nbd2  followed by Qc2 and long castling with a nice middlegame. }
8. g4 { Gaining space and firepower on the kingside. } 8... Qc7 9. g5 Nd7 10.
h4
{ with a very strong play on the kingside, showcasing the power of our Nimzo Larsen bishop. }
