{ Here my issues start 😀. Many people just have a strict and lazy repertoire and they just go for d5-Nf6-e6-Be7 against just every possible line 😀...But let's not judge them and I would even say 'Lazy people are not bad people' AD 2020. }
4. c4
{ We delay e3 move in order to have the option of going for our usual double fianchetto ideas. }
4... Be7 5. e3
{ We are in the epic candidates game between Karjakin-Anand 2016 where Karjakin introduced a new rage into systems involving the Nimzo-Larsen bishop. }
5... b6 { Black is also trying to activate his bishop via the fianchetto. } 6.
cxd5 { Restricting Black's options. } 6... exd5 7. d4
{ In this structure Black is better off developing the bishop on d6, hence he has to lose a tempi later on to play Bd6. }
7... O-O 8. Bd3
{ The best place for the bishop and we will have ideas involving Bf5. } 8...
Bb7 9. Nc3
{ The most active place for the knight and we can transfer it to g3 in order to provoke g6 which weakens Black's kingside. }
9... Nbd7 10. O-O Re8 11. Rc1 { The best place for the rook in this line. }
11... a6 12. Ne5
{ Not missing the golden chance to put the knight on e5 and continue with f4. }
12... Bd6 13. f4 { with a very sweet position and Black's best reply is } 13...
c5 14. Ne2
{ This is a very nice manoeuvre to bring the knight to the kingside, increasing the influence and also provoking g6 from Black which will eventually strengthen our Nimzo-Larsen bishop on b2. }
14... Rc8 15. Bf5
{ with slight edge and good pressure on the kingside and centre. } *

