5... Bg7 6. e3 O-O 7. c4 { We are threatening to win the a4-pawn with Nc3. }
7... d5 { Only way to try to defend the d5-pawn. } 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Bxg7 Kxg7
10. d4
{ with a big advantage for us. We forget about the a4-pawn and just happily accept our positional trumps of centre control, more active roles for our pieces. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Lasker, Em vs. Bauer, J."]
[Result "*"]

1. b3 Nf6 2. Bb2 d5 3. e3 e6 4. f4
{ Well guys, I have a confession to make...This wasn't how this position was reached in the origin game :@@EndBracket@@. I decided to change the move order of this sacred game in order to facilitate our selfish gains and to make it easier for our readers/viewers :@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Be7 5. Bd3 { The bishops come first! } 5... b6
{ One of the biggest events in 2020 was COB3  (Comedians on Board)  , during that time I taught the Nimzo-Larsen by showing them the Lasker game to one of my students Vaibhav Sethia who is a famous stand up comedian. Let's take a look at how he demolished his opponent by purely following the classics   5...O-O  6.Nf3  c5  7.O-O  b6  8.Nc3!  The knight has to be brough to g3 where it will help us in our attacking goals.  8...Nc6  9.Ne2  Bb7  10.Ng3  This is typical scenario where 'The student had surpassed the master'.  During one of my bullet games I went for the lame   10.a3  and deservedly lost the game :@@EndBracket@@.  10...Nb4  11.Be2  Nc6  12.Ne5!  Qc7  13.Nh5  Nxe5   13...Nxh5  was better of course, but let's not be very objective and just enjoy the show!  14.Bxe5  Qd8  15.Bd3!  Finally he had managed to recreate Lasker's immortal!  15...Nxh5  16.Qxh5   16.Bxh7+!  would have crowned the game even better!  16...Kxh7  17.Qxh5+  Kg8  18.Bxg7  Kxg7  19.Qg4+!  Bg5  Only move  20.fxg5  with a winning attacking for White.  16...g6   16...f5  would have kept the balance  17.Rf3  g6  18.Rg3  Bf6!  Just in time to stop all of our threats.  19.Rxg6+  hxg6  20.Qxg6+  with a perpetual.  17.Qh6  Bf6  18.Rf3!  The rook is heading to the h-file to deliver the final blow!  18...Re8  19.Rh3  Bg7  20.Qxg7  1-0 @@StartBracket@@20@@EndBracket@@ VaibhavSethia @@StartBracket@@1413@@EndBracket@@-Singlemayank @@StartBracket@@782@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com 2020 }
6. Nf3 Bb7 7. Nc3
{ I like the fact that the classical masters wanted to play with all their pieces! The knight is transferred to g3 where it will aid our evil ambitions. }
7... Nbd7 8. O-O O-O 9. Ne2 c5 10. Ng3 Qc7 11. Ne5 Nxe5
{ This is asking for trouble. } 12. Bxe5 Qc6 13. Qe2
{ To stop any d4 ideas and prepare to Bb5 just in case. } 13... a6 14. Nh5 Nxh5
15. Bxh7+
{ This is one of the most brilliant two bishops sacrifice ever played in a game!   15.Qxh5  would allow  15...f5  followed by Bg6 and Black is doing fine. }
15... Kxh7 16. Qxh5+ Kg8 17. Bxg7
{ The second bishop also sacrifices itself to break open the king's shelter. }
17... Kxg7 18. Qg4+ { Forcing the king to the h-file. } 18... Kh7 19. Rf3 e5
20. Rh3+ Qh6 21. Rxh6+ Kxh6
{ Black probably thought he had survived the worst...but Lasker had seen one move further. }
22. Qd7 { One of the bishops has to fall due to this cute double attack. }
22... Bf6 23. Qxb7 { The rest is just suffering for Black. } 23... Kg7 24. Rf1
Rab8 25. Qd7 Rfd8 26. Qg4+ Kf8 27. fxe5 Bg7 28. e6 Rb7 29. Qg6 f6 30. Rxf6+
{ Finishing the game in style! } 30... Bxf6 31. Qxf6+ Ke8 32. Qh8+ Ke7 33. Qg7+
{ Winning the rook and the game. } 33... Kxe6 34. Qxb7 Rd6 35. Qxa6 d4 36. exd4
cxd4 37. h4 d3 38. Qxd3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch, Aaron vs. Saemisch, Friedrich"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 c5 3. e3
{ This is the right move order, first we open up the bishop's diagonal. } 3...
Nc6 4. Bb5
{ With this we are more or less winning the fight for the control of e5-square. }
4... Bd7 5. Nf3 Qc7 6. O-O Nf6 7. d3
{ This is the classical way to play. More accurate and direct is  7.c4!  with a slight pull. }
7... e6 8. Nbd2 Be7 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 10. Ne5
{ The knight is very well placed on e5. } 10... O-O 11. f4
{ Bolstering the knight on e5 and preparing the rook shift to h3. } 11... Be8
12. Rf3 Nd7 13. Rg3 g6 14. Qg4
{ Bringing the next rook to the game via f1.   14.Qh5!?  was another interesting direction.  14...Nxe5  15.fxe5  f5!  16.exf6  Bxf6  17.Bxf6  Qxg3!  was maybe the reason why Nimzowitsch declined this tempting move. }
14... Bf6 15. Ndf3
{ All our cavalry are joining in on the fun to deliver the final assault on Black's king. }
15... Bg7 16. Rh3 f5
{ Panic!   16...h5  was more stubborn though we are clearly superior after  17.Qh4 }
17. Qh4 Nf6 18. Ng5
{ Black has to choose between giving up e6 or h7...both equally horrible :@@EndBracket@@. }
18... h5 19. Nxe6 Qe7 20. Nxg7
{ Note that Aron chose the bishop over the rook in order to make sure that our mighty warrior on b2 will be unmatched! Surprisingly even the usual greedy comp prefers this capture :@@EndBracket@@ maybe they have some hope after all? }
20... Qxg7 21. Rg3 { The rest is simple and requires no comments. } 21... Ng4
22. Qg5 Nxe5 23. Bxe5 Qh7 24. c4 Bf7 25. Qxf5 dxc4 26. bxc4 Rfe8 27. Qe4 Rad8
28. d4 cxd4 29. exd4 Kf8 30. Qxb7 Re7 31. Qb4
{ followed by Bf6 or Bd6 and finally winning the exchange. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Larsen, Bent vs. Kavalek, Lubomir"]
[Result "*"]

{ Time for one of the creators to teach us how to play this line 😀. } 1. b3 c5
2. Bb2 Nc6 3. c4 { I am so glad that Larsen also chose my direction! } 3... e5
4. g3
{ One of the points of delaying e3 or Nf3, we can do a double fianchetto now! }
4... d6 5. Bg2 Nge7 6. e3
{ In our course I recommend something like  6.Nc3  g6  7.d3  Bg7  8.Nf3  O-O  9.O-O  with the idea that the f3-knight will one day reach d5! }
6... g6 7. Ne2 Bg7 8. Nbc3 O-O 9. d3 Be6 10. Nd5 Qd7 11. h4
{ This is a very tempting direction! } 11... f5
{ A mistake! Black had to fight against the h5 move which opens the avenues for the h1-rook to join the attack.  The only reason I didn't recommend it is due to   11...h5  after which I didn't see how to improve our position further. }
12. Qd2 { Immediate  12.h5  was stronger with a clear advantage. } 12... Rae8
13. h5 b5 14. hxg6 hxg6 15. Nec3 bxc4 16. dxc4 e4 17. O-O-O Ne5 18. Nf4 Rd8 19.
Kb1 Bf7 20. g4 { Opening up the kingside with great vigour! } 20... Nxg4 21. f3
{ Continuing to destroy Black's defences. } 21... exf3 22. Bxf3 Ne5 23. Qh2
{ Mate incoming! } 23... Bxc4 24. bxc4 Nxf3 25. Qh7+ Kf7 26. Ncd5 Rg8 27. Nxe7
Rb8 28. Ka1 { A cool reaction, just walking out of the pin! } 28... Qxe7 29.
Qxg6+ Kf8 30. Ne6+ Qxe6 31. Bxg7+ { The cleanest! } 31... Ke7 32. Bf8+
{ What a way to end the game! } 32... Rbxf8 33. Rh7+
{ 33.Rh7+  Rf7  34.Rxf7+  Qxf7  35.Qxd6+  Ke8  36.Qd8 } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Fischer, Robert James vs. Andersson, Ulf"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following game is Fischer's first game with the Nimzo-Larsen Attack and he also showed us the way to play against 1...e5, hence it has historical significance  (assuming that my course changes the trend :)  . }
1. b3 e5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. c4 Nf6 4. e3 Be7 5. a3 O-O 6. Qc2 Re8
{ 6...d5  7.cxd5  Nxd5  8.Nf3  Bf6  9.d3!?  The best setup for us.  9...g6  10.Nbd2  Bg7  11.Rc1  Kasparov calls this the compressed spring method in his my great predecessors series!  11...g5  12.Nc4  Stronger was   12.h3!  f5  13.g3  followed by Bg2 killing Black's attacking ambitions with a clear advantage.  12...Qe7  13.b4  a6  14.Nfd2  f5  15.Be2  g4  16.Nb3  Kh8  17.Nca5  Nxa5  18.Nxa5  Qf7  19.O-O  c6  20.Nc4  Qe7  21.Rfe1  Bd7  22.Bf1  Nc7  23.Nb6  Rad8  24.Qc5  Qxc5  25.Rxc5  Ne6  26.Rxe5!  I wanted to show this game just for this typical Petrosian style sacrifice.  26...Bxe5  27.Bxe5+  Kg8  28.d4  with a clear advantage in @@StartBracket@@Petrosian-Sosonko Tilburg 1981@@EndBracket@@ }
7. d3 Bf8
{ The concept exhibitied by Ulf is slow and passive allowing Fischer to create a masterpiece in our line! }
8. Nf3 a5 9. Be2 d5 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nbd2 f6 12. O-O Be6 13. Kh1
{ Slowly and steadily Fischer starts his epic plan! } 13... Qd7 14. Rg1
{ Oh yeah!! This is how we play the Nimzo-Larsen! } 14... Rad8 15. Ne4 Qf7 16.
g4 { It was time! } 16... g6 17. Rg3
{ The plan shown by my hero is so cool and instructive at the same time! }
17... Bg7 18. Rag1
{ All our forces have been activated and it is time for the final phase of assault to begin. }
18... Nb6 19. Nc5 Bc8 20. Nh4 { Preparing some nasty Nf5 ideas. } 20... Nd7 21.
Ne4
{ It was in this position that I read some comments 'We have exchanged only one pawn so far, but our position is clearly winning, not everyday you witness something like this!'. }
21... Nf8 22. Nf5
{ The key blow winning the g7-bishop after which Black's defensive fortress will collapse like a house of cards. }
22... Be6 23. Nc5 Ne7 24. Nxg7 Kxg7 25. g5
{ Our bishop will have the last laugh! } 25... Nf5 26. Rf3 b6 27. gxf6+ Kh8 28.
Nxe6 Rxe6 29. d4 { The next bishop joins the fun :@@EndBracket@@! } 29... exd4
30. Bc4 d3 31. Bxd3 Rxd3 32. Qxd3 Rd6 33. Qc4 Ne6 34. Be5 Rd8 35. h4
{ One more pawn joins the war! Fischer's technique even in a winning position is top notch. }
35... Nd6 36. Qg4 Nf8 37. h5 Ne8 38. e4 Rd2 39. Rh3 Kg8 40. hxg6 Nxg6 41. f4
Kf8 42. Qg5 Nd6 43. Bxd6+ { and Ulf resigned due to the threat of f5... } *

