[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Fischer, Robert James vs. Tukmakov, Vladimir"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3 e5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. c4
{ This is our main direction...you could say I even got inspired by Fischer :@@EndBracket@@. }
3... Nf6 4. e3 Be7 5. a3 O-O 6. d3
{ 6.Qc2  is slightly more accurate  6...d5  7.cxd5  Nxd5  8.Nf3  Gaining a nice tempi attacking the pawn.  8...Bd6  9.Bd3!  One of the advantages of delaying d3. }
6... d5 7. cxd5 Qxd5
{ If Black goes for  7...Nxd5  8.Nf3  with a complex game. } 8. Nc3 Qd6 9. Nf3
Bf5 10. Qc2 { Preparing Rd1 to protect d3. } 10... Rfd8 11. Rd1 h6 12. h3
{ 12.Be2  followed by 0-0 was better. } 12... Qe6 13. Nd2 Nd7 14. Be2 Kh8
{ I think lack of active plans was the key point which lead to Black's defeat in this game. }
15. O-O Bg6 16. b4 { Starting the expansion plans of our kingdom. } 16... a6
17. Rc1 { Rearranging the rooks on the key open files. } 17... Rac8 18. Rfd1 f5
19. Na4 Na7 20. Nb3 b6 21. d4
{ Blasting open the position and Black's position quickly falls apart. } 21...
f4 22. e4 Nb5 23. Bg4 Qf6 24. dxe5 Nxe5 25. Bxc8 Rxc8 26. Rd5
{ A nice crush of a strong grandmaster! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Fischer, Robert James vs. Mecking, Henrique"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 c5 3. Nf3
{ As we have seen in our repertoire, the right way is to go for  3.e3!  Bishops comes first in our Nimzo-Larsen! }
3... Nc6 4. e3 Nf6 5. Bb5 Bd7 6. O-O
{ I have recommended   6.c4!?  in our prep as it felt more direct and immediately starts the fight for the center when Black is not ready for it. }
6... e6
{ Black is fine after  6...g6!  which was one of the reasons why I preferred 6.c4. }
7. d3
{ The concept shown by Fischer is in the one of the most basic setup for us. }
7... Be7 8. Bxc6 { It was time to take control of e5-square. } 8... Bxc6 9. Ne5
Rc8 10. Nd2 O-O 11. f4
{ Creating very nice kingside play which is powered by our Nimzo-Larsen bishop. }
11... Nd7 12. Qg4 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 Bf6 14. Rf3
{ Time to bring all our major cavalry to the fight! } 14... Qe7 15. Raf1 a5 16.
Rg3 Bxe5
{ Slightly better was   16...g6  though after  17.Bxf6  Qxf6  18.h4!  followed by h5 with a continuing attack on the kingside. }
17. fxe5 f5 18. exf6 Rxf6 19. Qxg7+
{ The rest is just amazing technique by Fischer. } 19... Qxg7 20. Rxf6 Qxg3 21.
hxg3 Re8 22. g4 a4 23. Nf3 axb3 24. axb3 Kg7 25. g5 e5 26. Nh4 Bd7 27. Rd6 Be6
28. Kf2 { Activating the king is always an important theme in endgames. } 28...
Kf7 29. Rb6 Re7 30. e4
{ Permanently creating a weakness on e5 which will become a target for the knight. }
30... dxe4 31. dxe4 c4 32. b4 Bg4 33. Ke3 Rd7 34. g6+ Kf8 35. gxh7 Rxh7 36.
Ng6+ Ke8 37. Nxe5 Bc8 38. Nxc4 Kd8 39. Nd6 Rg7 40. Kf2 Kc7 41. Nxc8 Kxc8 42.
Rd6
{ A strong display of power and dominance! Sadly this was Fischer's last game in the Nimzo-Larsen Attack! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Jobava, Baadur vs. Mamedyarov, Shakhriyar"]
[Result "*"]

{ The Nimzo-Larsen course wouldn't be complete without adding a game of the one of biggest exponent of our line! }
1. b3 Nf6 2. Bb2 g6 3. Bxf6
{ I steered clear of this direction for a specific reason.  One of Jobava's favourite development scheme is to play   3.Nc3  I think I have only recommended this type development very rarely in our courses. @@StartBracket@@Magician's path and copycat chapter@@EndBracket@@  3...Bg7  Black could have seized the advantage with   3...d5!  4.d4  and only now  4...Bg7  with a slightly better position for Black.  4.d4   4.Ne4!?  with equality.  4...c5   4...d5  was still enough to transpose to a slight advantage.  5.e3  cxd4  6.exd4  d5  7.Qd2  Nc6  8.O-O-O  Qa5  9.f3  h5!  Preparing Bf5.  10.Kb1  Bf5  11.Bd3  Nxd4  It is never a good idea to be greedy before finishing the development.  Shakh should have just continued with   11...Bxd3  12.Qxd3  e6  followed by long castling with a better position.  12.Nge2!  Nxe2  13.Qxe2  Bd7  14.Rhe1  e6  15.Bxg6!?  Full marks for bravery!  15...fxg6  16.Nxd5  Nxd5  17.Bxg7  Rg8  18.Qe5  Rxg7   18...Qc7!  was necessary with a winning advantage.  19.Rxd5  Qb4  20.Rd6  After this White takes over.  20...Kf8  21.Red1  Bc6  22.R1d4   22.Rd8+  would have won on the spot.  22...Rxd8  23.Rxd8+  Be8  24.Qf6+  Rf7  25.Qh8+  with a winning attack.  22...Qb5  23.Rd8+  Rxd8  24.Rxd8+  Ke7  25.Qd6+  Kf6  26.Qd4+  Kf7   26...Ke7  was still a draw!  27.Qf4+  Ke7  28.Qf8  1-0 @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ Jobava,B @@StartBracket@@2696@@EndBracket@@-Mamedyarov,S @@StartBracket@@2759@@EndBracket@@ Tbilisi GEO 2015 }
3... exf6 4. c4 Bg7
{ Bishop pair requires open diagonals and hence Black has to immediately fight for the center control with   4...d5!  5.cxd5  Qxd5  6.Nc3  Qd8!  Black has a very comfortable game and actually we are the ones who have to think about equality! This is the main reason why I didn't recommend this line in our course.   6...Qa5  allows some nasty ideas for White involving a3-b4.  7.a3 }
5. Nc3
{ If we get c4-Nc3 then we are doing great with an easy play since we can continue the light square domination with g3-Bg2. }
5... f5 6. Rc1 O-O 7. g3 Re8 8. Bg2 f4 { Trying to muddy the waters! } 9. gxf4
Qh4 10. Kf1 { But Jobava is not the guy you should mess around with! } 10...
Bxc3 { 10...Qxf4  11.Nd5  and the c7-pawn will fall. } 11. Rxc3 Qxf4 12. h4
{ White has a clear advantage already thanks to the kingside attack and comparatively more active pieces. }
12... d6 13. h5 Nc6 14. Nh3 Qd4 15. e3 Qf6 16. Nf4 Ne7 17. Qf3 Qg5 18. Bh3 c6
19. hxg6 hxg6 20. Bxc8 Raxc8 21. Nh5
{ Using even the king position on f1 wisely. } 21... f5 22. Rd3 Kf7 23. Nf4
Rcd8 24. Rh7+ Kf6 25. Qd1
{ and the queen goes to a1 to deliver the killer blow. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Rapport, Richard vs. Mista, Aleksander"]
[Result "*"]

{ Finally it is time to learn from one of the greatest creative players of the 21st century - Richard Rapport! }
1. b3 b6 { Copycat :@@EndBracket@@. } 2. e4
{ An important decision in order to throw Black off his lazy nature :@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Bb7
{ I have covered   2...e5  and other lines in more depth in the copycat chapter here. }
3. Nc3 e6 4. Bb2 c5 5. f4
{ An interesting and original direction  My recommendation and our path is   5.d4  cxd4  6.Qxd4  with a nice advantage. }
5... Nc6 6. Nf3 Nd4 7. Bd3
{ Thanks to the bishop development on b2, we can happily put our f1-bishop on d3 without having to worry about how to develop the c1-bishop! }
7... f5
{ Black is definitely not in a position to make any central demands like this! }
8. O-O Nf6 9. exf5
{ Of course sacrificing an exchange to attack the enemy king is a joke for someone like Rapport! }
9... Nxf3+ 10. Rxf3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Be7 12. g4 { Going for the kill! } 12... O-O
13. g5 Ne8 14. fxe6 dxe6 15. Qh3 { A nice double attack! } 15... Qd4+ 16. Kh1
g6 17. Qxe6+ Rf7 18. Bc4 Nd6 19. Bd5 Re8 20. Nb5
{ The brave bishop on b2 sacrifices itself to end the game! } 20... Qxb2 21.
Nxd6 Qxa1+ 22. Kg2 Rf8 23. Qxe7 { A nice game by Rapport! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Karjakin, Sergey vs. Anand, Viswanathan"]
[Result "*"]

{ We are gonna have a blast checking out Karjakin's cool display of power and dominance in one of the topical tabiya's of recent times. }
1. Nf3
{ In our repertoire we reach this line via   1.b3  d5  2.Bb2  Nf6  3.Nf3  e6  4.c4!  Keeping g3 options open just in case.  4...Be7  5.e3  reaching the main game. }
1... d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. b3
{ First time I came across this amazing line was by watching Karjak's epic game against our National hero Vishy Anand. }
4... Be7
{ 4...c5  5.Bb2  Nc6  6.cxd5  exd5  7.Bb5  My recommendation for our course is   7.d4  7...Bd6  8.d4  Getting the Isolani.  8...cxd4  9.Nxd4  O-O !  Black needn't waste time on protecting c6, since we really don't have the leisure of capturing it.  10.Nxc6   10.O-O  was the right way.  bxc6  11.Be2  was clearly worse for our guy @@StartBracket@@Karjakin-Wei Yi Medias ROU 2017@@EndBracket@@  11...Ne4  12.O-O  Qg5  followed by Bh3 with advantage.   4...b6  5.Bb2  Bb7  6.cxd5  Before Black decides to take on c4.  6...exd5  7.Nc3  Nbd7  8.d4  Generally this structure is quite favourable for us.  8...a6  9.Bd3  Bd6  This is one of Black's best setup, pay close attention to our QGD chapter since with some move order tricks I managed to avoid allowing this.  10.O-O  O-O  11.Rc1  Ne4  12.Rc2!  A nice manoeuvre.  12...Qe7  13.Qc1  13...Ndf6   13...Rac8  @@StartBracket@@Karjakin-Ganguly Kolkata 2018@@EndBracket@@  14.Ne2  with a complex game.  14.Ne2!  The knight is heading to g3 in order to provoke g6.  14...c5  15.Ng3  Nxg3  16.hxg3  Ne4  17.dxc5  bxc5  18.Bxe4!  dxe4   18...Qxe4  19.Ba3  winning the c5-pawn.  19.Nd2  Rad8  @@StartBracket@@Karjakin-Fressinet Doha 2016@@EndBracket@@ Here he should have played  20.Ba3  with a clear advantage. }
5. Bb2 O-O 6. Nc3 c5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qc2
{ After a while Karjak got tired of the move order nuances and just directly went for   8.h4  which is a decent alternative to our repertoire.  8...Nc6  9.Qb1  f5  10.Bb5  Bd7  11.h5  11...Nf6  This is silly, Black of course can't allow use to achieve h6 which makes sure that the bishop on b2 becomes a complete monster!   Black was better after the simple and prophylactic  11...h6  12.h6  g6  @@StartBracket@@Karjakin-So Abidjan CIV 2019@@EndBracket@@  13.Ne2  bringing the knight to f4 with a complex middlegame. }
8... Nc6
{ Once again Karjak used our Nimzo-Larsen concept of bishop to b2 to defeat Kramnik in the same year!   8...b6  9.Nxd5  exd5  10.d4  Nc6  11.Be2  Be6  12.O-O  Rc8  13.dxc5  Playing against the hanging pawns.  13...bxc5  14.Rac1  Qb6  15.Rfd1  Rfd8  16.Bd3  h6  17.Qe2  Nb4  18.Bb1  a5  19.h3  Qa6  20.Qd2  Qb7  21.Ba1!?  Preparing Qb2 ideas when the time is right!  21...Bf8  22.Qb2  f6  23.Nh4!  Going for the weakened light squares on the kingside.  23...d4  24.exd4  cxd4  25.Qe2  Bf7  26.Rxc8  Qxc8  27.Bxd4  with a healthy extra pawn which he converted convincingly in @@StartBracket@@Karjakin-Kramnik Moscow 2018@@EndBracket@@. }
9. h4
{ In our course I have recommended first   9.a3  which reduces Black's options. }
9... b6 10. a3 f5 11. Bb5 Bb7 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. d4 Rc8 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. O-O
{ This was the concept which amazed everyone...just cooly doing short castling after playing h4! }
15... Bf6 16. Rfd1 Ne7 17. Bxf6 Rxf6 18. g3
{ 18.Rac1  was stronger giving a big advantage, but this is the last time I will give the right way! Let's just enjoy the game without the scrutiny of comp. }
18... Ba6 19. Bxa6 Rxa6 20. Qc3 Rb6 21. Rac1 Qd6 22. Ne5 Rb7 23. Nd3 c4 24.
bxc4 Rxc4 25. Qe5 Qxe5 26. Nxe5 Rxc1 27. Rxc1
{ Thanks to the difference in pawn structures and activity of the pieces, White is clearly better in this endgame. }
27... g6 28. Rc5 Kg7 29. Ra5 Kf6 30. Nd3 Rc7 31. Ra6+ Kg7 32. Nf4 Rd7 33. Kf1
Ng8 34. Ne6+ Kf7 35. Nd4 Ne7 36. Nb5 Nc8 37. a4 Rb7 38. Rc6 Ne7 39. Ra6 Nc8 40.
Rc6 Ne7 41. Rd6 Rb6 42. Rd7 a6 43. Nc3
{ Thanks to this game, Karjak just infused a new found rage into not just this line, but also systems involving the development of the bishop to b2. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Karjakin, Sergey vs. Kramnik, Vladimir"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ Guys don't panic! This game is not directly relevant to our course, but it is not every day that you get to witness an elite player like Kramnik getting outplayed in a symmetrical structure. }
1... e6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 c5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nc3
Nc6 9. Bb2 { Whenever a bishop comes to b2 it has connections to our course! }
9... Nxc3 10. dxc3 Qc7 11. Qc2 b6 12. Bc1
{ I apologize for adding this game, this bishop will be better placed on f4. }
12... Bb7 13. Bf4 Qc8 14. Rad1 Rd8 15. h4
{ Preparing some Ng5 ideas and creating some play on the kingside. } 15... h6
16. Rxd8+ Nxd8 { 16...Qxd8  was better followed by Qe8 and Rd8. } 17. Rd1 f5
{ Asking for trouble, this weakens Black's structure to an unmeasurable extent. }
18. Qd2 { Invading along the d-file and the 7th rank. } 18... Nf7 19. Qd7 Bf6
20. Ne5 { A nice tactical shot! } 20... Nxe5 21. Bxe5 Bxe5
{ 21...Bxg2  22.Bxf6  Qxd7  23.Rxd7  gxf6  24.Kxg2  is a winning rook endgame due to the dominant rook on the 7th rank. }
22. Bxb7 Qxd7 23. Rxd7 Re8 24. Bc6 a5 25. Bb5
{ Karjakin's technique is top notch in this game. } 25... Kf8 26. f4 Bf6
{ 26...Bxc3  27.Rd3  winning the exchange. } 27. Rd6
{ One by one, Black's pawns start to fall. } 27... Re7 28. h5
{ Making sure that Black can't fix the kingside pawn structure. } 28... Bxc3
29. Rxb6 c4 { An unnecessary pawn blunder. } 30. Rb8+
{ Moving away from Bd4+ and then taking the pawn. } 30... Kf7 31. Bxc4 Rd7 32.
Kg2 Ke7 33. Kf3 Rd1 34. Rb7+ Rd7 35. Rb5 Rd1 36. a3 Rf1+ 37. Kg2 Rd1 38. e3 Rd6
39. Kf3 Rc6 40. g4 { Step by step, improving the position! } 40... fxg4+ 41.
Kxg4 a4 42. Rb7+ Kd8 43. e4 Bb2 44. Bb5 Rc7 45. Rxc7 Kxc7 46. bxa4 Bc3 47. e5
{ Gaining an important central passer. } 47... Kd8 48. Kf3 Bd2 49. Ke4 Ke7 50.
f5 exf5+ 51. Kxf5 Bc1 52. a5 Bxa3 53. a6 Bc5 54. Ke4 Ke6 55. Bc4+ Kd7 56. Kd5
Bf2 57. e6+ Kc7 58. Bb5 Bh4 59. a7
{ A classic masterpiece by my friend Karjakin! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Nepomniachtchi, Ian vs. Shirov, A."]
[Result "*"]

{ Nepo is the guy to follow in our course! Many times I have mainly recommended his direction. }
1. b3 { Let's have a look at how he was demolishing his opposition! } 1... d5
{ One of the main replies to our Nimzo-Larsen is   1...e5  2.Bb2  Nc6  3.Nf3!?  I really like this direction for shorter time controls and maybe classical...if you are sure that your opponent won't be well prepared.   3.c4  is our main direction.  3...e4  4.Nd4  Nxd4  Another topical reply is   4...Nf6  5.c4  5...Bc5  6.Nf5  We are definitely not going for   6.Nxc6  dxc6  7.e3  Bf5  Black already has a clear advantage.  8.Qc2  Qe7  9.Be2  O-O-O  10.f4  Ng4!  Initiating one of the greatest sequence involving the h-pawn and the rook!  11.g3  h5!  12.h3  h4!!  13.hxg4  hxg3  14.Rg1  Rh1!!  15.Rxh1  g2  16.Rf1  Qh4+  17.Kd1  gxf1=Q+  with mate in 3 @@StartBracket@@Larsen-Spassky Belgrade 1970@@EndBracket@@  6...O-O  7.e3  d5  The right way.  Nepo-Wesley Speed chess blitz 2020 continued   7...Re8  and here Nepo had the chance to create an absolute masterpiece with  8.Nxg7  N  Kxg7  9.Qh5  Gaining a crucial tempi attacking the bishop and threatening Qg5.  9...Be7  Only move and now comes  10.g4!  Kg8  11.Qh6!  Preparing g5.  11...d5  12.cxd5   12.g5  d4  gives the advantage to Black!  Nb4  13.Rg1!  with a clear advantage. We don't care about our anything on the queenside except our bishop :@@EndBracket@@.  8.cxd5  Qxd5  Black's only way to equalize is to play   8...Nb4!  9.Ng3   9.Qc1  N  In this position a novelty, though it might transpose to known lines.  9...Bb6  10.Ng3  Nfxd5  Correspondence players are shamelessly holding this position from Black :@@EndBracket@@!   10...Nbxd5  11.Nc3  with a more comfortable game.  9...Nfxd5!   9...Nbxd5  10.Nc3  with a slightly better position for us in  @@StartBracket@@Boehme-Firsching email 2012@@EndBracket@@  10.a3!?  Nd3+  11.Bxd3  exd3  12.O-O  I like our chances due to the potential play on the kingside using our only bishop and f4-f5 etc.  9.Ng3  9...Bg4  @@StartBracket@@Nepo-SL Narayanan Chess. com Blitz 2020@@EndBracket@@  10.Nc3!  Gaining a crucial tempi counter-attacking the queen.  10...Qe6  11.Qb1!  11...Rfe8  12.Bc4  with a clear advantage.  5.Bxd4  c5  This only plays into our plans!   5...Ne7  6.e3  d5  7.d3  7...Nf5  8.Bb2  Bb4+  9.c3  Bd6  @@StartBracket@@Nepo-Kobalia chess.com INT 2020@@EndBracket@@  10.dxe4  dxe4  11.c4  N  Opening the bishop's diagonal with a more comfortable game for us.  11...O-O  12.Nc3  Be5  13.Qxd8  Rxd8  14.Rb1!  with a nice endgame.  The refutation of this beautiful line is   5...d5  6.e3  h5!  But ok nobody is going to play this, unless he is prepared for 1.b3 and also in this specific sideline!  6.Bb2  d5  7.e3  Nf6  8.d3  exd3  9.Bxd3  Be7  @@StartBracket@@Nepo-Motylev chess.com INT 2020@@EndBracket@@  10.O-O  O-O  11.c4  with a slightly better position due to the kingside pawn majority and more active bishops.   1...c5  2.Bb2  d5  3.e3!  Of course Nepo is well versed in the move order nuances of the Nimzo-Larsen.  3...Nc6  4.Nf3   4.Bb5  is slightly more precise.  4...Nf6  5.Bb5  Bd7  6.O-O  e6  7.c4!  An important action to detail in the center.  7...dxc4  8.bxc4  with an interesting where he managed to overplay one of the greatest blitz players of all time @@StartBracket@@Nepo-Nakamura chess.com INT 2020@@EndBracket@@ }
2. Bb2 Bg4
{ 2...Bf5  3.d3!  Nepo has revived this forgotten direction!  3...e6  4.Nd2  The aim is to get e4 with minimal effort.  4...Nf6  5.g3  5...h6  6.Bg2  We are gonna get e4 and there is nothing Black can do about it.  6...Be7   6...Bh7  7.Nh3  7...a5  8.a3  c5  9.O-O  Nc6  10.e4  10...Be7  11.exd5  exd5  12.Nf4  O-O  13.Re1  Re8  14.Bxf6  Bxf6  15.Rxe8+  Qxe8  16.Rb1  d4  17.Nd5  Nepo had achieved a clear advantage which he managed to convert in  @@StartBracket@@Nepo-Aronian chess.com INT 2020@@EndBracket@@  7.e4  Bh7  8.Nh3  8...O-O  9.O-O  c5  10.exd5  exd5  11.Nf4  Nc6  12.Re1  Rc8  @@StartBracket@@Nepo-Svane chess.com INT 2020@@EndBracket@@   12...Re8  @@StartBracket@@Nepo-Aronian chess.com INT 2020@@EndBracket@@  13.Bxf6!  Bxf6  14.Rxe8+  Qxe8  15.Rb1  15...d4  16.Nd5  with a clear advantage thanks to light square domination.  13.Bxf6  Bxf6  14.Rb1  with a slightly better game due to the pressure on d5 and since playing d4 would always give us a huge advantage. }
3. f3 Bh5 4. h4
{ This is the stuff of legends and carries the true spirit of the Nimzo-Larsen! }
4... f6
{ 4...Qd6  5.Nh3  I recommend   5.d4!  in our course with the idea to put the king on c1 where it will be very safe :@@EndBracket@@.  5...f6  6.d4  Nc6  @@StartBracket@@Nepo-Artemiev chess.com INT 2020@@EndBracket@@  7.c4!  with nice play in the center. }
5. d4 c5 6. e4 { Opening up the center in a flash! } 6... dxe4 7. d5
{ I recommend   7.g4  in our course, but the game move is also pretty cool! }
7... exf3 8. Nxf3 e5 9. Nc3 Nd7 10. Qd3 Nh6 11. O-O-O Rc8 12. d6 c4
{ After this, White is just clearly winning.  Black had to go for   12...Rc6  13.Nb5  Qa5!  with a messy unbalanced fight. }
13. Qe4 cxb3 14. axb3 Qb6 15. Bb5 { 15.Nd5  was stronger. } 15... Bg4 16. Nxe5
{ Breaking through Black's feeble defences. } 16... fxe5 17. Qxe5+ Kd8 18. Qg5+
Nf6 19. Rhe1 { The mighty but sleepy rook joins the fight. } 19... Bd7 20. Nd5
{ Black has no chance of survival. } 20... Rxc2+ 21. Kxc2 Bf5+ 22. Qxf5
{ Nice one :@@EndBracket@@. } 22... Qc5+
{ 22...Nxf5  23.Bxf6+  with a mate in 6. } 23. Kb1 Nxf5 24. Bxf6+ Be7 25. dxe7+
{ With that mini masterclass we come to the end of our epic course! } *

